issuenote: A disagreement between two families turns into a machete and gun fight.

A government party activist is killed in connection to an upcoming election.
An ARENA activist is killed in the latest of a series of political killings in advance of the elections.
FMLN activists throw stones at an ARENA rally, striking a candidate for the legislature in the eye.
Violence erupts after an ARENA rally.
People looted an abandoned truck of soda, and onlookers then mobbed the looters, trying to pull soda bottles out of the boxes for themselves.
Seven Tojolobal Indian men are shot to death and thrown in a deep cave after neighbors accuse them of rustling cattle.  Their bodies are not recovered until February.
A mob of villagers burn two men accused of stealing cattle.  One of the victims dies.
A mob murders two suspected robbers.
A mob of enraged villagers drags a man from his jail cell and hangs him after he was caught with a stolen pig and burro.
A mob kills a man accused of stealing a statue of Mary Magdalene.
A former paramilitary member was beaten and macheted to death and at least 20 homes of suspected military supporters were sacked or burned.

The office of a human rights group is robbed and vandalized.

target: Brian Williamson - Jamaica's best known gay rights activist
issuenote: Williamson hacked to death by attackers with machetes at his home.
Gooden was shot and killed at his mother's home.
Man shot and injured during period of political violence.

Peasants moved back onto land claiming to have been illegally seized, sharecroppers came and threw the peasants off the land they were trying to claim; later in the day, the local rural sheriff and his deputy came to Piate, and eight people were killed.

Seven people were killed and at least 50 wounded by unknown assailants following a campaign rally; the Movement to Organize the Country party headquarters also was broken into by three men and the offices ransacked.

2 people were killed in election-related violence.

Gunmen in a car killed two men in area loyal to People's National Party.

Armed men rob a bus.

Revolutionary party activist shot and killed in confrontation with Liberation party followers.

Militant from DRP was killed in partisan violence, 2 others killed in other incidents.

A political activist is murdered in the latest of a string of political slayings in advance of elections.

A prominent human rights lawyer is found dead, and a note left on her body warns that the same could happen to others.

target: INITE ruling party candidate Jude Celestin supporters

Supporters and opponents of Daniel Ortega clash after his reelection.
Assailants shoot dead an Indian activist.

Two men open fire on an indigenous group that attacked illegal loggers a year prior.  The activists were on their way to investigate reports of illegal logging when they were attacked.
Gunmen opened fire at JLP event, one killed.
A Labor Party poll watcher was killed in a voting station clash. Residents set up flaming roadblocks, 3 killed during violence.
One man was killed during a political rally as rival party supporters clashed.
Aristide supporters attacked opposition protesters; each side threw rocks at each other and one person was injured and five people were detained.
A small group of pro-government demonstrators and politicians was chased away from the streets by rock and bottle-throwing opposition supporters, injuring seven people.

Opposition activists charging election fraud clash with supporters of the PRI.  Event begins as sit-ins at 33 town halls, but then escalates to rioting.

Zapatistas and PRI supporters clash over land ownership.

A mob contests the re-election of mayor Pablo Escobar and clashes with his supporters.
Several military regime supporters were killed in retaliation for an earlier crackdown on pro-Aristide demonstrators.
An activist with the Guatemalan Republican Front is gunned down in advance of elections.
Two groups of political supporters clashed and one person was killed.
Violence between party supporters led to several deaths.
Rival supporters clashed outside of ballot counting center, wielding knives and throwing stones.

Scattered riots erupt the day after an election.
Government and rebel supporters clash.

Gunmen attack and rob a group of American volunteers.

A campaign worker for a vice presidential candidate is shot to death on a busy street.

A Haitian migrant was decapitated, after allegedly killing a local merchant.
Men ran through the streets, firing gunshots into the air and burning cars along the road.

Bus drivers were protesting that some workers had not received severance pay when replaced by private bus workers.

Teachers were protesting the upcoming 7-Jun-15 elections and other unspecified reasons related to teacher requirement reforms. There was also mention that the teachers were protesting in relation to the 43 missing students from 26-Sep-14, but reports don't indicate any direct connection between the events.

Exiles flew over Havana distributing leaflets criticizing Castro, urging peaceful protests against regime.

10 wives of imprisoned political dissidents protested calling for the release of their husbands and the protest was disrupted by uniformed police who forced the protesters onto buses and took them home.

400 peasants block several major highways, demanding the government fulfill promises to build health clinics, promote cattle ranching, and build roads.  Another group protests high electricity prices.
Peasants hold demonstrations in honor of the 1910 Mexican Revolution and to show support for the EZLN.  Protests escalate to riots, and police use tear gas.
Ethnic Maya peasants clash with police to show support for a local newspaper editor and former gubernatorial candidate.
A protest caravan makes its way to Mexico City to protest the loss of PRD candidate in Tabasco's gubernatorial election.
Hundreds of farmers ride their tractors into the main square to call for a nationwide moratorium on payments of past-due agricultural loans.
EZLN rebels break a cease fire and occupy a town, ransacking the town hall and burning government archives.  Government troops enter town and make a show of force, re-occupying the town.
30,000 people protest over an economic crisis, which led to a massive devaluation in the peso.
500 well-dressed demonstrators march on the presidential palace to protest austerity measures.
Tens of thousands of PRD supporters protest against the president's policies toward the Zapatistas.
Thousands stage an anti-war protest in support of a peaceful solution to the Chiapas conflict.
Debtors surround the Interior Ministry to protest soaring interest rates.
Protestors clash with police and soldiers over the arrest of a former city councilman.
3000 teachers march to demand pay increases.
Tens of thousands protest against government austerity.
150,000 marchers protest the devalued peso, layoffs, high taxes and interest rate hikes associated with the Mexican financial crisis.
Hundreds of peasants blockade the stock market, led by the losing candidate in the prior year's gubernatorial race in Tabasco state.
Unemployed garbage collectors and laid-off bus drivers march against the ongoing economic crisis, demanding the government give their jobs back.
Thousands of stall owners march in response to rumors that the government will privatize public markets.

Several thousand people rally on the anniversary of a 1968 student massacre.  The protest quickly turns into a rally about economic conditions; the protesters beat up two motorists and hijack and burn several buses.
300 protesters gather outside a courthouse as a rebel leader is arraigned.
Protesters march against proposed changes to the social security system.
Protesters march against proposed changes to the social security system.
Protesters march against proposed changes to the social security system.
Students, unionists, and various organizations gather to protest a wave of privatizations and to show support for the Zapatistas.
Protesters rally against government handling of an air pollution emergency.
Protestors march through Mexico City, claiming the government has abandoned middle class debtors.
PRD supporters march against plans to privatize several oil wells and to demand compensation for environmental damage caused by oil operations.
PRD supporters march against plans to privatize several oil wells and to demand compensation for environmental damage caused by oil operations.
PRD supporters march against plans to privatize several oil wells and to demand compensation for environmental damage caused by oil operations.
15,000 people march to protest against the privatization of a petrochemical plant.
Indigenous Mexicans launch a hunger strike to prod the federal government to offer them social programs, aid, and farm land.
Over 100,000 protestors takes to the streets on May Day to protest against currency devaluation and unemployment.
Teachers protest for higher pay.  Police crack down violently.  The police chief is eventually fired for the incident.
Protesters block streets demanding the withdrawal of army troops mobilized into the countryside, particularly in the hills of Guerrero, Oaxaca, and other states.
Thousands march on Columbus Day in favor of indigenous rights.
Activist priests and peasants ambush police in apparent retaliation for the eviction of peasants who had seized lands in the region.
Thousands of people march to demand the release of two jailed priests arrested in connection with the deaths of two police officers.
Protests occur across Mexico to honor Emiliano Zapata.  Protesters consist in Indians demonstrating over ethnic issues and land distribution.
Teachers protest for higher pay.
Zapatista supporters burn election materials and ransack voting stations to protest an election.
Thousands of rebels and their supporters march from San Cristobal to Mexico City to press for greater Indian rights.
Students march to demand a full government accounting for a 1968 massacre of hundreds of peaceful demonstrators.  Several people are injured when marchers attack cars, buses, and loot stores.
Thousands march against Columbus Day.  Mayan natives demand land and the fulfillment of government peace promises.
Thousands march against Columbus Day.  Mayan natives demand land and the fulfillment of government peace promises.
Thousands march against Columbus Day.  Mayan natives demand land and the fulfillment of government peace promises.
Children lead a protest in front of the president's official residence, protesting the recent massacre in Acteal.
About 400 Indians march to Acteal to demand punishment of government officials they accuse of complicity in the massacre there.
4000 people march on the fourth anniversary of the Zapatista uprising and mourn the death of 45 people in Acteal.
4000 people march on the fourth anniversary of the Zapatista uprising and mourn the death of 45 people in Acteal.
Hundreds of townspeople protest against journalists and the government over arrests made in the town, denying that anyone in the town was responsible for the Acteal massacre.
Zapatista supporters protest against the Acteal massacre, and then clash with police in Ocosingo.  Police open fire, resulting in one death.
Zapatista supporters demand punishment for police officers who fired on demonstrators.
Zapatista supporters gather outside government office buildings and shout at soldiers on the day of a funeral for a woman shot dead at a protest.
Conatram initiates a strike to demand that the government resolve a number of labor issues.
3000 Indians protest on the anniversary of Emiliano Zapata's death.  They demand democracy and land rights for Indians.
Indian organizations march through Mexico City's Zocolo market to demand an end to second class status for Indians, better land distribution, and the removal of the military from Chiapas.
50,000 telephone workers stage a two hour walkout to protest a new 15 percent tax on telephone services.
Thousands camp outside the Congress to protest against the president's budget during a time of financial crisis.
Members of the armed forces in full military dress marched through the streets of Mexico City, protesting against the naming of a defense minister without consultation of active generals.
Rebel sympathizers march to commemorate the one year anniversary of a massacre in Acteal.
30 protesters camp outside the Monument of Independence, and then gather outside the stock exchange to demand changes in the government's policy in Chiapas.
Hundreds of ethnic Indian rebel supporters march to celebrate the anniversary of the Chiapas uprising.
More than 100 alleged leftist rebels held in a prison stage a hunger strike to demand the liberation of all political prisoners in Mexico.
15,000 people march to Mexico City to protest alleged electoral fraud.
Barefoot Tzotzil Indian women march in Acteal to demand peace in Chiapas.
Dozens of women march to demand police action against a wave of rapes and murders.
Thousands of students protest a tuition hike at National Autonomous University.
100,000 people march to protest against privatization of the country's electricity system.
Thousands of leftist party activists black streets in an effort to stop the inauguration of a new governor.

Thousands of students strike to protest tuition fees and take over about 40 schools throughout the UNAM university.  The students regularly stage massive demonstrations.  The strike eventually widens to include unionists and teachers.
Teachers protest to demand salary hikes.
14,000 union members protest government plans to increase private investment in the state owned electric power industry.
600 police protest for higher pay.  During the march, protesters recognize a police commander in civilian clothes and beat him up.
Prisoners stage a small riot over a recent flood that inundated the prison.
Hundreds of people block a highway to protest sandbagging that they say compounded recent flooding.  Police beat and arrest many of the protesters.
Rebel sympathizers commemorate the Zapatista rebellion.
Hundreds of riot police march to demand salary increases and the dismissal of their commander.
Thousands of people march to protest the deployment of security forces seeking to prevent students from seizing the UNAM university over the Easter break.
20,000 teachers protest to demand salary increases and prompt payment of salaries.
3000 police officers march to protest the failure of the government to pay them a bonus and to demand an end to corruption.
More than 8000 people march in a gay pride parade and demand equal rights.
PAN supporters attack vote counting offices, burning 85000 ballots.
PAN supporters attack vote counting offices, burning 85000 ballots.
PRI supporters try to storm an electoral office, clashing with police.
More than 100 employees of the transportation ministry strike to protest their transfers to other jobs.  Clashes erupt with police.
Hundreds of police march to protest the detention of four colleagues who shot and killed a thief during a gun battle.
Thousands march to commemorate the 32nd anniversary of the day a security battalion opened fire on student protesters.
Workers hold a rally to protest a recent recommendation by the national antitrust watchdog that the state owned airline Cintra be split up and privatized.
A group of Canadian and American peace activists stage a hunger strike in favor of the Zapatistas.
Members of an EZLN splinter group dash into a town on the edge of Mexico City, fire guns into the air and spray graffiti on buildings.
The EZLN stages a protest and marches from San Cristobal to Mexico City to lobby for an Indian rights bill.  The march is led by Subcommandante Marcos himself.

1500 ranchers and small land owners march to protest land seizures by the Zapatistas.

Farmers and ranchers, backed by Lacandon Indians, protest to demand that Congress modify an Indian rights bill advocated as a peace measure with the Zapatistas. Protesters demand the return of land seized by rebels.
Teachers strike and protest nationwide for higher salaries.
Mayors representing all three of the major political parties gather with thousands of residents to protest an Indian Rights bill, which they say is inadequate.
Indians groups protest against an Indian rights amendment to the constitution as it passes the state legislature.  Indians claim it will not bring the peace it is intended to bring.

Zapatista supporters seize six Secretary of Social Development officials and demand expanded federal benefits. 300 police officers then storm the town and liberate the hostages. Two days later, peasants protest against excessive use of force.
Zapatista sympathizers block a highway in Chiapas to protest the passage of a watered-down Indian rights bill.
Thousands of farmers protest government farming policies, which has depressed coffee, sugar, and grain prices.
A few dozen protesters gather outside a meeting of WTO trade ministers.
Human rights organizations demonstrate outside government offices, protesting the possibility that federal prosecutors could take over the investigation into the killing of a human rights lawyer.
Machete wielding farmers organized by the PRD march through the city streets to protest the expropriation of their land for a new international airport.
40,000 teachers strike to demand that President Vicente Fox increase federal funding for education.
Residents erect sandbag barricades and dig trenches to prevent land expropriation and construction of an airport in the area.
Protesters demonstrate against a plan to expropriate land for an airport.  American activists join the protest and are expelled from the country by the government.
600 pig farmers block an international bridge on the US border to demand that the government offer them the same subsidies that US farmers receive.
15,000 Mayans protest against the government's infrastructure development plan.
2000 Zapatista supporters wearing ski masks march through the streets, demanding that a government agent they claim killed a Zapatista leader be handed over to them.
Thousands demonstrate on Columbus Day against racial discrimination.
About 100 angry farmers block a US border bridge and dozens more demonstrate in Mexico City against the lifting of tariffs on agricultural products stipulated by NAFTA.
About 100 angry farmers block a US border bridge and dozens more demonstrate in Mexico City against the lifting of tariffs on agricultural products stipulated by NAFTA.
Antigovernment protesters disrupt congressional midterm elections by smashing windows, blocking the installation of polling stations, and beating townspeople who turn out to vote.
Hundreds of demonstrators close down a bridge on the border to protest WTO talks in Cancun.
Several thousand students and political activists march to mark the 35th anniversary of the student massacre in 1968.
A group closely related to the PRI organizes a protest against the government's plan to open the energy sector to private investment.
Demonstrators march in Mexico City and dozens of cities around the world, calling on the Mexican government to respond to the killings of hundreds of women in Chihuahua state over the last decade.
80,000 union members, left wing activists, and farmers march to protest plans to raise taxes on food, medicine, and to sell state-owned assets.
Wives and relatives of some of Mexico's criminals and suspects hold a protest to demand better prison conditions.
Braceros demonstrated against the government.
Jane Fonda, Sally Field, and Christine Lahti lead a march, urging the government to provide sufficient resources to help investigate the killing of hundreds of women in the last decade.
50,000 supporters of Mexico City mayor Obrador protest against government officials accusing him of corruption.
Hundreds of protesters march to show support for the Cuban government, one week after President Vicente Fox tells the Cuban ambassador to leave Mexico. They decry the government and condemn the US.
Dairy farmers, with cows in tow, protest in front of the US Embassy to call upon the Mexican government to subsidize the production of milk.
Six Basques accused of belonging to the ETA stage a hunger strike to protest an order for their extradition to Spain.
Thousands of union workers protest reforms to the country's social security system.
Some 3000 protesters march through downtown and past the US embassy to mark the 51st anniversary of the July 26 uprising in Cuba.
Mexico City's leftist mayor leads about 200,000 protesters in a march to protest efforts to impeach him and uses the event to unveil his 2006 presidential platform.
Thousands of students, union leaders, and activists march to commemorate the anniversary of the 1968 student massacre.  Police clash with a group of anarchists before the protest begins.
Mexicans who worked in the US during a World War II guest worker program, and their heirs, protest to demand restitution of pension funds.
Hundreds of thousands of PRD supporters march to protest the prosecution of Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador.
Hundreds of teachers take to the streets during negotiations with the government over salary increases.
About 200 members of a religious group walk to the presidential residence to demand that the government reinstate the sect's registration, allowing it to raise money and own property.
More than 10,000 sugarcane growers march to protest plans by the president to veto a sugarcane bill passed by the Congress.
Thousands of sugar workers strike and take over mills throughout Mexico's 15 sugar-producing states in order to protest the federal government's opposition to a new production law.
Miners strike for better working conditions and to show support for a union leader accused of responding poorly to a mining tragedy.
Cubans riot at a prison to demand that they not be deported back to Cuba.
Hundreds of machete wielding farmers stage a two day blockade of a pumping plant to protest government plans for a dam on a waterway.
More than 100 people blockade a highway to protest police brutality at a recent riot.
Thousands of people, led by the leader of the Zapatistas, take to the streets to claim that the elections that are underway do not offer a real solution to the country's problems.
Thousands of Lopez Obrador supporters gather to protest announcements declaring Felipe Calderon the winner of the recent election.
More than 200,000 supporters of leftist presidential candidate Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador protest his defeat in the election.

Lopez Obrador supporters gather outside each of Mexico's 300 electoral districts and begin marches on the capital in order to demand a ballot-by-ballot recount after the recent election.  The protesters gather in the capital.
Supporters of a leftist presidential candidate blockade the stock exchange and then march to the president's residence.

500,000 supporters of leftist presidential candidate Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador march to demand a vote-by-vote recount of the recent election.  Protesters camp in the central square for weeks.  Some protesters stage violent riots.
Lopez Obrador supporters protested against the government after the courts ruled that Felipe Calderon was the winner of the election.
More than 5000 demonstrators march through Mexico City to commemorate the 1968 massacre of protesters.
About 300 Mazahua Indians briefly take over a water treatment plant to demand more government development aid.
Tens of thousands of trade unionists, farmers, and leftist groups march to protest price increases for basic foods like tortillas.
Miners across Mexico stage a 24 hour strike, hoping to achieve better safety standards and to improve labor's footing in the industry.
Two Mexican guerilla groups demand the release of political prisoners by bombing a Pemex gas pipeline.
A teacher's union demonstrates against proposed changes to the government pension system, briefly closing down the international border.
Hundreds of leftist activists march to demand the government provide information on the whereabouts of two members of a rebel group who went missing in May.

Thousands of white-clad demonstrators protest against government plans for a partial privatization of the state-owned oil company.
Tens of thousands of fishermen on both of Mexico's coasts keep their boats in port to protest against rising fuel prices.
More than 500,000 truck and bus drivers stage a one day strike to press for lower diesel fuel prices.

Protesters march, claiming that the president is exploiting an outbreak of H1N1 swine flu for political purposes, noting that campaigning for congressional mid-term elections is due to start soon. Clashes occur.
150,000 people protest against the surprise closure of a state-run power company.
Thousands of Mexicans rally to show support for Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador, charging that the 2006 election was stolen from him.
Over 1000 people march through Juarez to call for authorities to end the city's bloodshed.
Two electricians go on a hunger strike for three months to protest the government's shutdown of a power company.
Thousands of protesters march to demonstrate against widespread violence connected to the drug trade.
Dozens of Mexican women march to demand that the authorities find missing sons and daughters who have disappeared during the drug war.
Tens of thousands of people march to demonstrate against the inability of authorities to end a crime wave.
More than 20000 teachers and students march and block roads to demand the release of 98 protesters arrested during a clash with police in the prior week.
2000 people march to demand the releaseof 70 people held following the violent protests that occurred during the presidential inauguration.
Thousands of indigenous Zapatista supporters march to commemorate the Dec. 22, 1997 massacre of 45 Zapatistas, and to celebrate the end of the Mayan calendar.

Teachers angered over education reforms protest in the streets.  After the protest, dozens run wild, storming the offices of the PRI.  They also attack the PAN, PRD, and Citizen Movement party headquarters.

400 people gather to march for justice and to demand an end to attacks on the press.  Many hold up posters suggesting the government had a hand in the recent death of a journalist.  Dozens also protest in Mexico City.

Students violently demonstrate against a decision to issue student identity cards in order to exempt them from public transport fees.  The students claim the cards are really to make it easier for the government to track student leaders.

Public employees strike over increasing transportation and electricity prices.
Protesters demonstrate against Vice President Espina, who has been declared president by the military after Jorge Serrano was deposed.

Protesters gather around the country to demand government help for poverty stricken farmers and to demand rights for indigenous peoples.  Unidentified gunmen open fire on one gathering, killing a protester.  Protesters riot.

Protesters demonstrate against a proposal to increase sales taxes and to add taxes on some businesses, with protesters accuse the US of pressuring Guatemala to approve the taxes. Protests escalate to riots and clashes and police repress.
Nine students begin a hunger strike at the supreme court to protest a tax increase.
53 air traffic controllers strike for higher wages.
Hundreds demand punishment for those responsible for massacres during the civil war.

Protesters call for the resignation of the president and vice-president.

Violent protests erupt in support of former dictator Efrain Rios Montt, after the supreme court suspends his presidential campaign.  Protesters riot, surrounding the court, government offices, and the US embassy and a journalist is shot dead.
Ex-paramilitaries hold hostage four journalists to press the government for compensation for participating in the civil war.
About 100 organizations mobilize tens of thousands to strike, block highways, schools and other services to protest plans for a tax hike.
Paramilitaries protest outside of Congress to demand compensation for their services during the civil war.
Air traffic controllers strike, shutting down air travel in Guatemala.  The government eventually fires the strikers.
8000 teachers, unionists, farmers, leftist politicians, and academics wage massive street protests against the pending Central American Free Trade Agreement.
Hundreds of protesters try to break through police and storm the Legislative Palace in an effort to stop the passage of the CAFTA pact.
Protesters denouncing CAFTA clash with police in the capital, and stage scattered riots around the country.  Gunfire erupts on a highway in the northeast, leading to the death of one protester.
Catholics are unable to pray for Pope John Paul II because the church is closed due to a demonstration against CAFTA.
Guatemalans protest against CAFTA.  Simultaneous protests occur in many of the Central American states.
Riot police use tear gas to clear protesting families of the civil war dead who were demonstrating against a celebration of the armed forces.

Thousands of indigenous protesters protest against the killing of protesters by security forces in an earlier protest.
Several dozen people protest outside a prison against the genocide conviction of former dictator Efrain Rios Montt.
Attorney General replaced due to staying in office longer than ruled legal.

Public health workers strike and riot for higher wages.  Event ends when the army removes the striking workers from the hospitals.
Two indigenous persons imprisoned for destroying a statue of Christopher Columbus on 10/12/1997 stage a hunger strike.

Indians protest on Columbus Day against a decision to strike down a law that bans foreigners from buying land along Honduras' borders and coasts. Many Indians live in these areas and fear being driven out by foreign investors.
A strike occurs over plans by the government to privatize state-owned businesses.
Protesters of the Chorti tribe block the entrances to a tourist site, demanding that the government give them land to farm.  Police forcibly remove them.
School teachers strike to demand the government pay their salaries and increase wages.

Indigenous peoples block a road to protest the deforestation of their communities.

Doctors and nurses strike at public hospitals for higher wages.
Indigenous protesters take over a tourist site to pressure the government to honor a 1997 deal to disperse land to the Indians.
Environmentalists protest laws that allow foreign investment in Honduran mines; they argue that foreign capital destroys the environment.
Indians protest the construction of a hydroelectric dam.
Armed protesters clash with police, demanding that the government build more schools, health clinics and provide other services in the area.
An anti-poverty protest sets up a roadblock.  A hotel owner loses his patience with the blockade and opens fire on the protest, killing a teacher.
Thousands of pro-Zelaya protesters take the streets for the first time since Honduras' new, post-coup president was inaugurated.
Protesters mark the one year anniversary of the coup.
Pro-Zelaya protesters call for the ousted president's return and a 15pct wage hike.

Pro-Zelaya protesters and teachers strike, demanding Zelaya's return and protesting a law decentralizing education.  Zelaya had promised the teachers a pay-raise, but that was canceled after the coup.  Violent riots occur on the 16th.
Security forces use tear gas to break up a demonstration involving some 100 journalists protesting the murder of 17 colleagues in the past two years, and demanding justice from the government.
Farming activists occupy land for which they claim ownership rights under a government reform program.  Police evict the farmers, leading a clash and one injury.
Farming activists occupy land they claim they have the rights to under a government reform program.  Police arrive and arrest the activists.

Protesters burn down government offices and demand that US drug agents leave the area.  The protests are a reaction to an anti-drug operation in which it is claimed that drug police and US agents killed four people.
About 1800 police officers strike for higher pay and better working conditions.  They block several streets with their patrol cars.
800 people demonstrate in support of a leftist presidential candidate who claims to have won a recent election.  Police respond by beating protesters and using tear gas.
More than 5000 people led by a leftist presidential candidate and her husband, a former president overthrown by a military coup, march to support an opposition presidential candidate.
500 Salvadorans gather to remember a massacre of Jesuit priests in 1989.
Demobilized soldiers clash with police in front of the presidential palace to demand that the government fulfill its promises of land and cash for their demobilization.
Social security workers strike for higher wages, occupy their office buildings, and clash with police.  The police use tear gas.
An organization of war veterans seizes a building, takes hostages, and demands that the government release prisoners jailed during the civil war.  Violence occurs when the police storm the building.
Civil war veterans and government employees demonstrate for higher pensions, land, or credits.  In Santa Ana, they occupy the mayor's office.

Doctors and social security workers block streets to protest privatization schemes in the health-care sector.  Police use tear gas and rubber bullets.
Bus drivers strike to demand increased diesel subsidies and cheap credit for bus purchases.
Truck drivers block highways to demand that the government pressure oil companies to lower gas prices.
Bus drivers strike to protest against new regulations that they say favor competing mini-bus drivers.
Doctors at state hospitals strike to protest privatization.  On 2/20/2003, they riot, storming the social security building.  The doctors are eventually fired.
Masked protesters occupy a cathedral to protest a scheme to privatize health care.
Students protest the war in Iraq, and their government's support of it.
Activists protest the war in Iraq, and El Salvador's participation in free trade talks.
Doctors block roads and hunger strike to be allowed to return their jobs, after having been fired for striking.
Doctors and union members protest to be allowed to reclaim their jobs, after they had been fired for striking.

Dozens of street vendors protest against plans by the government to confiscate pirated music and movies.

Students clash with police in riots over electricity rates and public transport fees.

Veterans protested their lack of pensions and other benefits.
A militant, pro-Sandinista public employee's union strikes for higher wages.   The strike ends with a doubling of salaries and promises by the government not to fire the strikers.

Two gunmen on a motorcycle drove up and opened fire at candidate Jean-Laurent Nelson, and he was struck with a machete.
Chamber of Deputies candidate Milo Gousse was shot and his driver was killed after gunmen blocked a highway and opened fire on his car.
Far-right candidate Vladimir Jeanty was threatened by an armed group of people when he tried to hold a rally.

target: Candidate for Prime Minister Edward Seaga
issuenote: Rival political gangs exchanged gunfire, at least 14 killed during 3 week campaign and on election day.
Two candidates for office from the Enceuntro Por Guatemala Party are killed by assailants with automatic weapons.
No issue was overtly stated for this apparent assassination, but AFP alluded to election disagreements during his run in the mayoral race.

Teachers march on Congress as it debates educational reforms.  The teachers attempt to force their way into the legislative chamber, triggering a riot and a clash with police.  Thousands then gather and blockade the Congress.

Demonstrators demanding the resignation of Haiti's electoral council and for longer voter registration periods demonstrated and some threw stones at cars and burned street vendors' stalls, with four killed.
Molotov cocktails were tossed at elections council buildings around Port-Au-Prince.
Gunmen entered electoral council headquarters and demanded to see council member Jesse Manigat and left when confronted by security guards.
Electoral materials were burned.
A bomb went off outside an electoral office, but no one was injured.
Someone threw a grenade into the compound of Haiti's electoral office, slightly damaging the structure.
Two gunmen riding in the back of a pickup truck opened fire on electoral offices, hitting an electricity transformer.
A scuffle erupted at a voting station when a candidate accused electoral officials of trying to influence voters.
A scuffle erupted at a voting station.
Protesters threw boxes of unused ballots into muddy streets after election officials announced they didn't have enough ballots to conduct the vote.
Several provincial electoral offices were shut down by demonstrators protesting that electoral officers are pro-government.
Youths, claiming that electoral officials failed to pay them for their work during the election, smashed car windows and set fire to a wooden barrier.
Mobs prevented the delivery of voter registration materials and set fire to a senator's office.

target: Federal Electoral Tribunal and headquarters of PRI
issuenote: Simultaneous explosions hit several locations.  A coalition of leftist guerrilla groups claims responsibility, demanding that the governor Oaxaca resign, whom they accuse of rigging the 2004 election and oppressing dissent.
Thousands of protesters took to the streets to demand that national elections be scrapped and some protesters threw rocks at police who fired back tear gas.
Thousands of protesters took to the streets to demand that national elections be scrapped and some protesters threw rocks at police who fired back tear gas.
Supporters of presidential candidate Mirlande Manigat vandalized electoral offices

More than 10,000 protesters called for Rene Preval to be declared the winner of Haiti's presidential election over 5 days of protests; on the third day of protests, a protester died from gunshots after peacekeepers opened fire.

More than 10,000 protesters called for Rene Preval to be declared the winner of Haiti's presidential election over 5 days of protests; on the third day of protests, a protester died from gunshots after peacekeepers opened fire.

More than 10,000 protesters called for Rene Preval to be declared the winner of Haiti's presidential election over 5 days of protests; on the third day of protests, a protester died from gunshots after peacekeepers opened fire.
Armed men stole ballot boxes after the polls closed.
Nine citizens broke into Belgian ambassador residence seeking asylum.
Citizens invaded residence of Belgian ambassador in effort to win asylum, held protest appealing for help.
What are thought to be members of the National Congress of Democratic Movements firebombed the building housing election ballots, and 25-36 members were arrested.
Protesters storm the lower house of Congress on horseback, and occupy the legislative chamber for more than an hour. Teachers at the National Coordination of Education Workers demand higher wages.
PRD legislators storm the lower house of Congress and seize the speaker's podium to prevent discussion of proposed funding changes for local education.  This occurs three days in a row.
Thousands of PRD supporters led by Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador protest a Congressional vote stripping him of immunity from criminal prosecution.
Protesters gather and throw rocks at police to protest the passage of a pension reform bill.  Police respond with tear gas.
Abortion opponents summoned by Mexico's Catholic Church march through the capital to protest bills that would legalize abortion in the first three months of pregnancy.

Tens of thousands of protesters gather outside the Senate to protest the passage of a pension reform bill.  Some of the protesters fight with police, using sticks and bottles.  Police strike back with pepper spray and baton charges.
300 unionists take over the Congress building to protest a law that would make it illegal for private sector employees to strike.
Protesters demonstrated against the Congressional resolution that there was no genocide during the Civil War.
Lawmakers brawl on the floor of Congress after opposition legislators threaten to block the inauguration of Felipe Calderon.
The five members of the party (not elected officials) were killed before polling stations opened and the report indicated that the two events were related.
Revolutionary party supporters protested split in party by violently demonstrating near Congress.
Seven killed in election day violence.
Seven killed in election day violence.
A retired Royal Canadian Mounted Policeman who traveled to Haiti to help peacekeepers was killed when gunmen fired on his vehicle.
Protesters angry about the partial closure of Haiti's border with Dominican Republic set fire to a Haitian immigration office and police shot and wounded a youth.
People raided the local police station, chased off a half-dozen policemen, stripping one of his clothes, and pounded the police station to the ground with sledgehammers.
A crowd accused police officers of committing human rights abuses and mobbed their patrol vehicle.
Dozens of residents of a mountainside community scuffle with police after walking out of talks aimed at ending a land dispute with residents of Santo Tomas Ajusco.
Violence occurs between police and citizens attending a PRD election rally.
Unknown gunmen with automatic weapons kill three policemen and a bystander in three separate attacks during statewide elections.
Residents of Cheran detain 16 police in an office to demand an investigation into an armed attack the day before.
Aristide supporters broke into a national police arms locker, loading their vehicles with weapons.
Several policemen protesting unfair promotion selection criteria interrupted an examination for precinct chiefs.
A police force trainee swearing in was broken up by about 500 people who accused the inductees of being linked to the military and forced them to flee.
An off-duty police officer was shot and killed for unknown reasons by gang members, three of whom were also killed.
An off-duty police officer was shot and killed for unknown reasons by gang members, three of whom were also killed.
Hijackers killed 2 policeman in attempt to seize ferryboat to escape Cuba, 4 attempts occurred over 2 weeks.
About 100 demonstrators threw rocks at police headquarters, a former torture site.
About 300 demonstrators burned down a courthouse, threw rocks at and tried to set fire to a police station after a police officer shot and killed a suspected criminal.
A mob torched cars and vandalized a provincial police station and burned down a house to protest an off-duty police officer's alleged killing of a civilian.
Protesters smashed the windows of passing cars and set fire to street merchants' stalls to protest the killing of Michelange Philistin, 25, who was shot in the head.
Members of the anti-government Artibonite Revolutionary Resistance Front engaged in a shootout with police, and one Front member was shot and killed.
Shooting broke out between police and armed militants from the Arbonite Revolutionary Resistance Front.
Members of the Arbonite Revolutionary Resistance Front exchanged gunfire with police, and a taxi driver passing by was shot and killed.
Members of the anti-Aristide militant group Artibonite Revolutionary Resistance Front exchanged gunfire with police, and one passerby was killed.
People threw rocks at police and street battles occurred between the Gonaives Resistance Front and police, with between three and seven police killed and a couple of other people also killed.
Residents blocked streets throughout St. Marc to prevent policemen from entering the city and one person was shot and wounded by police.
Flaming barricades were set up to prevent police from entering the city.
Flaming barricades were set up to prevent police from entering the city.
A protest was held against the police.

Police fired tear gas and used batons and fired shots while Marines blocked the entrance of a police academy as thousands of job hunters stormed the building during a recruiting drive; one person was killed from being trampled.
Former soldiers wearing military uniforms killed 4 police officers while they were on patrol and stole two machine guns, four shotguns and a radio.
More than 2,000 Aristide supporters staged a peaceful demonstration, accusing police of killing two men during a recent protest.
Thousands of Aristide supporters, including many women claiming that police had killed their sons, marched to protest alleged police killings.
A small group of protesters threw rocks at police and peacekeepers.
Police clashed with residents of a displaced persons camp demanding that they vacate and the eviction became violent when residents refused to evacuate.
Protesters were calling for the President's and Vice-President's resignation.
Protests took place against 2 police killings during strike the previous day.
Youths staged violent demonstration to protest killing of gang member Juan Carlos Mateo.
Shootout ensued between gangs and police during police crackdown on drug-related crime.
Umbrella organization protested arrests of activists in advance of announced general strike.
Demonstrators violently protested killing of man by police, 2 citizens killed.
Referees' Association refused to work remainder of season due to increasing violence at matches involving attacks on players and referees.
Clashes occurred between police and residents in opposition stronghold in capital, 4 people killed.
Supporters of Phipps blocked roads with flaming tires, attacked security vehicles, burned an armored police bus.
Rioters blocked road, burned police cars, and threw rocks at police to protest shooting of taxi driver
Thousands attended funeral paid for by JLP for those killed in police raid.
Citizens blocked intersection to protest police shooting of Wedderburn, gunmen & police exchanged fire during incident.
Dozens of citizens marched and created roadblocks to protest police killing of Linton Rodney.
Residents protested and blocked roads, set fire to 4 buiildings in response to police killing of boy.
Thousands rioted to protest police shooting of two men, buses were burnt and roads blocked.
Hundreds rioted, attacking police station and burning cars after student shot by police.
Residents burned debris and blocked roads to protest police killing of 3 men.
Inmates rioted at prison over complaints that they were denied visits.
Residents temporarily blocked streets with trash in protest of Shaw killing.
Shooting of baby by police led to protests.
Man trying to see PM over tax issue slashed police officer's throat.
Residents of Tivoli Gardens built barricades to guard against extradition attempt of Coke.
Residents of Tivoli Gardens built barricades to guard against extradition attempt of Coke.
Residents demonstrated outside police station to protest extradition of Coke.
Police stations attacked as police & gangs fought across city over extradition of Coke, 60 killed. State of emergency declared.
Police stations attacked as police & gangs fought across city over extradition of Coke, 60 killed. State of emergency declared.
Police stations attacked as police & gangs fought across city over extradition of Coke, 60 killed. State of emergency declared.
Police stations attacked as police & gangs fought across city over extradition of Coke, 73 civilians and 3 security officials killed. State of emergency declared.
Citizens mounted roadblocks and marched in protest of police killing of two men.
Police were striking about their low wages.
Villagers blocked a road to protest a rise in kidnappings and police response.
300 Indian peasants block a highway and set a police car on fire.
Thousands of transport drivers protest government decision to declare a bus line insolvent and lay off its workers.  They also protest the arrest of the driver's union.
Street vendors clash with police over a ban on illegal commerce in the city square.
100 residents of the Buenos Aires neighborhood of Mexico City rally outside a police state to rally against police brutality.
Workers at a wholesale produce market clash with police in a dispute over a newly imposed entry fee.
Hundreds of prisoners take over a prison to protest flood inundation and food shortages.

Students take over a school over claims that state officials are profiting from the proceeds of school lands, they are arrested. Angered by these arrests, activists surround dozens of police officers and hold them hostage.
Opposition party farmers and police clash in a fight over a warehouse full of construction material.

Riots erupt in the Tepito neighborhood after a police raid seizes seven trucks loaded with stolen merchandise. Angry shopkeepers and residents clash with police, and looters take over the streets that night.
Auxiliary police upset at not receiving a bonus block streets in the capital and fire their guns, clash with regular police.

Farmers and their sympathizers protest the expropriation of land to build an international airport; clash with police in Santa Catarina.  After the riot is pacified, another group of farmers seize hostages in San Salvador Atenco.

Farmers and their sympathizers protest the expropriation of land to build an international airport; clash with police in Santa Catarina.  After the riot is pacified, another group of farmers seize hostages in San Salvador Atenco.
Police evict squatters living illegally in an ecological reserve, triggering a riot.
Gunmen ambush police, sparking a gun battle, at the site of a long-running religious dispute between Indian-style Catholic traditionalists and Evangelical Protestants.
Dissidents and leftist sympathizers clashed with police, and police killed one.
An angry crowd briefly takes a hostage and clashes with police as they try to quell a local land dispute.
Police attempting to evict 200 squatters from a plot of land are greeted with gunfire, sticks, and stones.

Villagers take over the entrance to some ruins, protesting excessive entrance fees and a lack of investment in the area.  In October, police attempt to remove the villagers, triggering a violent riot.
No specific reason was provided for these killings.
Suspected criminals and police engaged in a fight for unknown reasons and it appears there were two gangs involved.
This was a gang attack, but no specific reason was provided for this shooting.
Blind protesters were demonstrating against the ban on selling goods at a specific location in the historic center of Mexico City.
The Gulf cartel protested the arrest of leader  Antonio Hato Maya.
Teachers and parents of the missing 43 students were protesting the upcoming elections.
Protesters were demonstrating against the sexual attack and murder of a woman.
Students throw rocks at police to demand the release of 40 colleagues arrested at a protest.
Bus drivers clash with police to demand better security.

Opponents of a Canadian-owned gold and silver mine project seize 23 police officers and hold them hostage.  Security forces move in, resulting in a clash in which one officer is shot dead.  Riots spread into nearby towns.

Opponents of a Canadian-owned gold and silver mine project seize 23 police officers and hold them hostage.  Security forces move in, resulting in a clash in which one officer is shot dead.  Riots spread into nearby towns.
Street vendors clash with police, who try to remove them from downtown San Salvador, where vending is illegal.
Contras continue to make demands on the government, demanding promised land and the resignation of Sandinista officials; Contras attack a police post and battle the Sandinista army.
Small groups of ex-Contras hold up banks and police posts, stealing money and guns.
Small groups of ex-Contras hold up banks and police posts, stealing money and guns.
Former Contra rebels attack police and seize control of a town, killing 2.
150 to 200 Recontras and former Sandinistas take over Esteli over demands for land, prompting several days of war with military forces.
Criminals trying to rob a store open fire on police, resulting in a firefight.
Farmers were protesting against farm owners demanding that they pay medical bills for kidney problems the farmers believe developed because of their work on the farms.
A police station was pillaged and U.S. troops prevented the lynching of Corporal Mondelus Norelus, a notorious torturer.
Three police stations were attacked by a group calling themselves the 'Base Resistance.'
Three police stations were attacked by a group calling themselves the 'Base Resistance.'
Three police stations were attacked by a group calling themselves the 'Base Resistance.'
Gunmen burned down the home of Gonaives police chief Harold Adeclat, whom protesters accuse of complicity in Cannibal Army leader Amiot Metayer's killing.
The Arbonite Revolutionary Resistance Front fired on the Gonaives police station from a passing car and then approached on foot, spraying the building with bullets and two police officers' houses.
A police station and mayor's house were attacked by the Gonaives Resistance Front, killing 11.
Armed Aristide opponents seized the police station, firing into the air and chasing away police and also burning down the courthouse; two people were killed.
Armed men occupied the police station in Anse Rouge and several other town outside Gonaives and confiscated weapons.
Armed men occupied the police station in Anse Rouge and several other town outside Gonaives and confiscated weapons.
A police station was attacked and burned down by Aristide opponents.
Residents burned down the police station in Dondon and police launched counter-attacks and wounded two rebels.
Insurgents torched the police station and police launched a counter-attack, wounding two rebels.
An armed group burned down a police station.
Armed men burned down a police station.
Arsonists burned down a police station.
Armed men attacked the police station and torched the building and seized two all-terrain vehicles belonging to a non-governmental organization.
An armed group attacked a police station.
Recontras attack a police station to demand land.
A policemen was shot and killed by supporters of a minor party candidate who was arrested on charges of election fraud.

A mob set up flaming tire barricades, torched vehicles and overran and looted the police station to protest the reported release of a bus driver accused of involvement in an accident that killed 17 carnival revelers.
Former Contra rebels attack a Sandinista police post.
Labor related unrest.  Sugar workers leave a pro-Sandinista union and join the Nicaraguan Workers Union.  Workers attempt to march on Managua, but are stopped by the Sandinista controlled police.

State police take four people into custody, including a local justice of the peace.  A group of residents claim the authorities did have  warrants and retaliate by hurling stones, trash, and the taking of hostages.  Police use tear gas.
Protesters attempt to march downtown to demonstrate against bank foreclosures and high interest rates.  They are beaten by police, and a congressman is injured.
Armed gangs trapped a group of U.N. civilian police behind a flaming barricade and disabled their armored personnel carrier in a two-hour gunbattle.
Soldiers occupied plant  after threatened shutdown due to government debt to company.
Flight attendants strike against the national airline over working conditions, benefits, and salaries.
The 1500 member airline stewards union, ASSA, strikes to demand a salary increase.
Flight attendants at Mexico City's international airport strike for higher wages.
300 Mexican environmentalists and farm activists protest outside a meeting of agricultural researchers to decry the importation of genetically modified corn.
38 flight attendants went on strike to protest company's lack of a viable business plan.
38 flight attendants went on strike to protest company's lack of a viable business plan.
200 people lit candles, sang hymns and marched through a park to protest Alcoa Inc.'s proposed US$1.5 billion aluminum smelter, saying it will harm the environment and its neighbors.
A camp of up to 50 people kept a vigil, fearing the construction of an aluminum smelter will damage the environment and endanger residents who mainly work in farming or fishing.
Fired miners blockade a road into the American Pacific mining company.  Army troops try to remove the protesters, resulting in clashes and one civilian death.
Villagers who say they suffered from psychological and property damage from detonations unleashed by a Chinese petroleum exploration company hold 50 workers hostage to demand compensation.
Employees of a banana company strike over a dispute over raises for workers in packing sheds.
Workers walk off the job at the state-owned telecom company, demanding higher wages from the government.
Workers at Ford plants strike over a company announcement that there will be no profit-sharing this year after losses in 1996.
Workers at Ford plants strike over a company announcement that there will be no profit-sharing this year after losses in 1996.
Workers at Ford plants strike over a company announcement that there will be no profit-sharing this year after losses in 1996.

Members of an actors union responsible for dubbing the Spanish language version of The Simpsons strike after the company, Grabaciones y Doblajes Internationales, seeks out additional non-union actors for the project.
Fishermen riot to demand access to an estuary on Martima company property.  They clash with police, and one of the fishermen is killed.

Leftist lawmakers storm both houses of Congress and seize control of their chambers to protest an energy bill that would make it easier for the state oil company to seek outside assistance in developing oil fields.
Fishermen from five unions seize a distribution center in response to a decision by the national oil company to stop selling diesel fuel at industrial prices.
Leftist protesters march to protest a bill in the Senate that would open the state oil company to private investment.
3 of Jamaica's 4 foreign-owned alumina refineries went on strike demanding higher wages and fringe benefits.
Attackers killed assembly candidate Merilus Deus and slashed his daughter with a machete in their home.
Comando Jaramillista Morelense 23 de Mayo attacked banks.
Citizens looted businesses in midst of flooding caused by hurricane.
Residents went on general strike to protest mining firm's pollution and public services, escalated to clashes with police.
Two candidates for the Central American parliament are assassinated.

target: Chamber of Deputies candidate Jean-Charles Henoc
issuenote: Jean-Charles Henoc, candidate for the Chamber of Deputies, was shot twice in the head and killed.
The teenage daughter of a congressional candidate is murdered.

target: Haitian Democratic Party candidate Lesly Tilus
issuenote: Haitian Democratic Party mayoral candidate Lesly Tilus was kidnapped and released three days later.

target: Home of presidential candidate Danilo Medina
issuenote: Shots were fired at home of Medina, security returned fire.
A leftist candidate for office is shot dead in front of his home.
Arsonists torched the home of legislature candidate Jeremie Joachim.
Four gunmen kidnapped city government advisory board candidate Claudy Myrthil in front of his home; he was found severely beaten on May 2.
A mayoral candidate for San Agustin Acasaguastlan is shot dead outside a pharmacy in Zacapa.
A congressional candidate is assassinated in advance of elections.
The Charlot Jacklin Militant Front surrounded the headquarters of Alternative Party for Development in Haiti and threatened to burn it down unless they received money and stoned the building.
Gunmen fired at the home of an opposition presidential candidate, shattering a sliding glass door.
A PAN mayoral candidate is shot dead.  The suspect is his PRI rival.
An unidentified gang attacks a PRI candidate for mayor.
A candidate for governor is assassinated, along with four other people.
Candidate Rudolphe Pierre was struck on the head by a rock.
20 young men and women hurled rocks and shouted insults at the motorcade of presidential candidate Dumarsais Simeus and a shot was fired.
Gunmen opened fire at a rally for presidential candidate Michel Martelly, killing one person and injuring several others.
Celestin supporters threw tear gas and shots were fired at a rally for presidential candidate Mirlande Manigat.
Protesters march in silence, praying for peace and unity during the presidential elections.
A stone-throwing commando broke up a rally for a Senate candidate, injuring one person.
A mayor and candidate for the Senate is assassinated.

target: Supporters of opposition candidate Edward Seaga
issuenote: Rival supporters of Prime Minister and JLP candidate Edward Seaga engaged in shootout, injuring 12 people.

target: Supporters of presidential candidate Danilo Medina
issuenote: Clash occurred in front of Liberation party headquarters between supporters of two candidates, shots fired.

target: Supporters of presidential candidate Miguel Vargas
issuenote: Four people killed in a clash between partisans in runup to election.
A candidate for the town council is shot dead.
Three men from the National Front for Change and Democracy assaulted candidate Gerda Colas.
Aristide gangs looted two car dealerships and set them on fire.
Former paramilitaries storm the Central Bank, demanding compensation for their participation in the war.  Police use gas and rubber bullets.
More than 400 unionised Central Bank workers went on strike, claim lack of cash access is impacting operations.
290 workers strike to demand increased compensation when their plant closes at the end of the year.
Cattlemen march in protest and also seize leader of Mexico's Southeastern Human Rights Association, accusing them of encouraging peasants to stage land invasions.
Gunmen raid a children's hospital and steal guns from the guards.
Banana workers strike to protest new fruit quality standards that deprive them of pay bonuses.
Banana workers strike for higher wages.  Refinery workers stage a solidarity strike.  The strike ends when the army removes the strikers.
Banana workers strike for better wages.
Banana workers strike to demand wage hikes and more social services.
Banana workers strike to demand wage hikes and more social services.
4500 employees strike at the Chiriqui Land Company for higher wages.
About 300 protesters threw rocks and a molotov cocktail at a cholera treatment center because they feared that the clinic would bring more of the disease to Haiti.
Workers at Chrysler plants across North America strike, affecting plants in Mexico, Michigan, and Indiana.
Workers at Chrysler plants across North America strike, affecting plants in Mexico, Michigan, and Indiana.

A small leftist group plants explosives at five branch banks recently purchased by Citigroup. Several of the devices explode, but no one is killed. The leftist group is angered because the banks were bailed out by taxpayers.
A mob takes hostages inside City Hall to protest the construction of a golf course that resident claim will damage the environment and their small-town lifestyle.
Workers staged a brief strike to demand a new labor contract.
Thousands of teachers and activists demonstrate over lax public safety in schools.
A bar was set ablaze, and nearby shops were looted, along with a private food warehouse.
Businesses announced they were refusing to pay electricity bills due to power outages.
A bomb is exploded at a Catholic church.  Sandinistas are blamed.
Sandinistas bomb a Catholic church.
A church is bombed on the eve of the Pope's visit.
Catholic church buildings are dynamited.
Catholic church buildings are dynamited.
A church is bombed.
Unknown gunmen ambush nuns traveling in a car.

target: Christ for the Nation (Dallas) church evangelists
issuenote: Crowd gathered around evangelists, upset at claim that schoolgirl was pricked with needles by white strangers.
PNP supporters who earlier quarreled with JLP backers fired at church on election day.
Inmates took 43 nuns hostage to demand improved prison conditions and removal of administrators from posts.
Unknown kidnappers (speculated to be leftist Colombian guerrillas) kidnap three missionaries of the New Tribes Mission.
Stone-throwing crowds attacked Catholic Relief Services  workers as they prepared to distribute food.
As United States warships appeared off the coast of Haiti, armed civilians shot into the air and broke up a church service.
Attackers attacked an army outpost.

Army forces arrive at a base to arrest members of the Zorros for the massacre of six teenagers. Police take over their own base and barricade themselves inside to protest the arrests. Zorros surrender after 14 hour standoff.

A mob seizes control of an army outpost in protestover the construction of a hydroelectric plant.  The mob also demands justice for a man killed hours earlier for what they claim was an attempt to intimidate them.
Indians in Chiapas protest the re-installation of a military camp.

Military police mutiny for an improved compensation package for post-war demobilization.  They claim that the rebels got a better deal and then refuse to leave their barracks, exchanging gunfire with government troops.

target: Former top official of Haiti's 1991 military coup government
issuenote: A former top official of Haiti's 1991 coup government was machine-gunned to death along with another person after announcing the formation of a new political party.
Aristide supporters protested against the military.
About 5,000 pro-democracy Haitians marched to army headquarters demanding that Cedras step down and also leave Haiti.
Rock-throwing demonstrators advanced on military headquarters to protest the alleged deaths of prisoners at the hands of Haitians soldiers.
People marched past army headquarters with pictures of Aristide.
Haitians waved branches and played musical instruments outside Cedras' mansion and marched to the airport to celebrate his departure from Haiti.
A voodoo priest and another person were killed and at least ten houses and five stores linked to members of the military were set on fire and a grain depot was looted.
Hundreds of discharged soldiers massed at army headquarters demanding their salary for December and payment of pensions.
Discharged soldiers rioted then protested against the military.
About 1,500 protesters marched around the Presidential Palace, demanding that Haiti's army be disbanded; scores of demonstrators later broke into the Ministry of Commerce.
Pro-Aristide demonstrators demanding that supporters of the former Duvalier dictatorship be disarmed set up burning tire barricades and a mob burned two houses of presumed supporters of the army.
Pro-Aristide demonstrators demanding that supporters of the former Duvalier dictatorship be disarmed set up burning tire barricades and a mob burned two houses of presumed supporters of the army.
Pro-Aristide demonstrators demanding that supporters of the former Duvalier dictatorship be disarmed set up burning tire barricades and a mob burned two houses of presumed supporters of the army.
Mexican army and EZLN rebels clash.
Zapatista activists staged a protest. Indian peasants build roadblocks in several areas.  Mexican army and police retake the area the next day.
Zapatista activists staged a protest. Indian peasants build roadblocks in several areas.  Mexican army and police retake the area the next day.
3000 Indian rebel sympathizers march to a town to protest the military deployment there.
Rebels claiming to fight for economic and social justice clash with military forces.
EZLN rebels and the government clash in an Indian village after the rebels began setting up their own government.
Pro-Zelaya protesters violently denounce the military coup; anti-Zelaya protesters demonstrate.
Pro-Zelaya protesters flock to a border crossing to support Manuel Zelaya's bid to reclaim the presidency.  There, they clash with police.
Public health workers strike to demand the return of president Zelaya.

Baton-wielding police fire tear gas to chase thousands of demonstrators away from the Brazilian embassy, where the deposed president is holed up.  The demonstrations continue for days, and two are killed by police.
A small protest in favor of Manual Zelaya occurs.
Over 100 protesters gather in the hotel where crisis negations are underway between supporters of Zelaya and supporters of the coup.
Police fire tear gas and water at pro-Zelaya demonstrators who are protesting post-coup elections.
Police fire tear gas and water at pro-Zelaya demonstrators who are protesting post-coup elections.
Angry civilians have stoned officers in streets according to former air force pilot.
A presumed military supporter was stabbed to death by protesters; some of these protestors then began searching cars looking for weapons.
Gunmen attack US Army soldiers in a humvee during a visit by President Bush.  The incident occurs on a highway connecting Panama City to Colon.
Unknown assailants throw a bomb at a fuel storage facility operated by the US military.  A bomb squad disables the device.

About 1000 Cuban refugees riot at the Empire Range Complex of refugee camps.  The refugees are angry with the slow pace of resettlement.  236 US soldiers are wounded in the rioting.  The US soldiers specifically avoid taking hostile action.
Three snipers belonging to a leftist group open fire on a bus carrying 28 US airmen.
13 far-left political and grass-roots organizations staged a protest against foreign troops in Haiti and plans to sell state-owned companies.
About 2 dozen supporters of Jean-Claude Duvalier disrupted a news conference about abuses during his rule, shouting down representatives of Amnesty International.
Police killed two after taking gunfire from suspects of a drive-by shooting previous night.
About 100 student supporters of a recently ended student strike march through campus and clash with anti-strike students.
Contract negotiations end in a strike.
Five hundred demonstrators block bridges between Mexico and the US to protest the presence of Mexico's armed forces in the area.
Shots were exchanged between armed rebels and armed residents, when the residents thought they were being denied food rations.
Unknown gunmen rob an armored car outside a Sam's Club.
A group of about 15 men open fire on an armored car as its guards drop off money at a currency exchange office.
Armored vehicle fired upon while clearing car from intersection in area barricaded by Coke supporters.
The mob attacked Juracan and burned him to death in response to his murder of a political rival, Lorenzo Sequen.
Street vendors protest against changes in bus routes which they say will hurt their businesses.  They blockade a road, but then gunmen on motorcycles attack them.

Gang members try to extort protection money from bus drivers.  In southern Guatemala, they attack a bus, resulting in two deaths.  In the capital, they throw a grenade onto a bus, wounding 11 security guards.
May Day protest against CAFTA.
Protesters decry the official beginning of the CAFTA pact.
Indians hold a rally/prayer meeting to exhort civil war combatants to make peace on the eve of a visit by the Pope.
Recontra bandits take over rural roads, rob coffee growers and vehicles.
Recontra bandits take over rural roads, rob coffee growers and vehicles.
Hundreds of peasants throughout northern Guatemala seize 14 coffee plantations to protest the unfair distribution of land.
University students protest outside the Colombian embassy, calling on that government to condemn a Colombian military attack on a rebel base that left four Mexican students dead.
Native peoples gather to protest Columbus Day.  They smash a statue of the explorer in Colon Plaza.
2000 protesters watch as a Indian rights group finishes a three month symbolic trial of Christopher Columbus.  The group finds him guild and 'executes' him by pelting a painting of him with arrows.
More than 1000 protestors, many dressed in Indian costumes, march to protest Columbus Day and to demand indigenous rights.
Indigenous peoples protest against Columbus Day.

target: Community of Latin American and Caribbean States (CELAC) conference
issuenote: Government dissidents arrested opposing CELAC.
A homemade bomb causes a mid-air explosion on a commuter plane, which then crashes into the mountains, killing 21 people.  The dead include 12 Jewish businessmen and the mayor of Colon.
Construction workers strike for better wages.
Farmers seize six workers, including a Bulgarian engineer, in protests over land expropriation for an airport.
Workers demanding wage increases from subcontractors halted the construction of a natural gas plant.

Protesting workers shut down a construction project at a natural gas plant; strike lasts approximately ten weeks; hundreds of these striking workers also staged a demonstration at Port-of-Spain, demanding higher wages.

Protesting workers shut down a construction project at a natural gas plant; strike lasts approximately ten weeks; hundreds of these striking workers also staged a demonstration at Port-of-Spain, demanding higher wages.
Public transit workers blocked buses from serving routes to protest Conurban tranferring routes to government.

target: Copacabana, Chateau, Triton hotels and a bar
issuenote: Explosions rocked 3 Havana hotels, one tourist killed. Govt claims U.S. involvement.
Landless peasants invade a corporate farm, resulting in the death of a guard.
Dozens of residents protest and block streets around the site of a former cultural center where Costco plans to build a store.  Riot police arrive and arrest many of the protesters.

Four gunmen, including two in army uniform, sprayed the Council of State with gunfire, leading to two deaths; it was believed this was meant to block the government from holding presidential balloting.
More than 100 citizens march to protest the deaths of hundreds of women in the last decade, and the recent sexual abuse and slaying of a 7-year old girl.
Thousands of white-clad demonstrators protest against a surge of drug-related violence in Cuidad Juarez.
More than 8000 people gather to protest a wave of violence that has afflicted the city in recent weeks.  They are led by the state's governor.
500 women march to protest against the murder of female protestor outside a government office.
About 500 people stage a four day silent march to protest drug violence, marching from Cuernavaca to Mexico City.  They are joined by more protesters in Mexico City.
About 500 people stage a four day silent march to protest drug violence, marching from Cuernavaca to Mexico City.  They are joined by more protesters in Mexico City.
Drug trading in the National Penitentiary leads to a battle among prison gangs using smuggled guns.
About 600 teachers strike after being subjected to extortion.
Two men hijacked border guard vessel to try to reach Florida.
Raid by anti-Castro group intercepted by security forces, fisherman died during raid.
15 armed men shot and killed 4 victims in Golden Villas, stronghold of PNP in apparent retaliation for previous night's shooting.
Opposition demonstrators clash with police over Daniel Ortega's attempt at another term.  Consecutive terms had previously been banned, until the Supreme Court lifted the ban in 2009.
President Medina stated he was open to running in the new election, sparking protests.
A leftist legislator, a Jesuit priest and two former rebel commanders stage a hunger strike to demand the dismantling of the death squads that have arisen after the civil war.
Carter and Ellis were killed in shootings triggered by recent elections.
Sandinista peasants clash with demobilized Contras in a land dispute.
Unknown attackers murder the leader of a political party in advance of a referendum on constitutional reform.
Prison guards staged a strike to protest poor working conditions under Prescod and renewal of his contract.
At least six knife-wielding assailants stabbed deputy mayor Johnny Charles.
Student supporters of the PRD throw eggs at the PAN candidate.
Hundreds infected with HIV protest against discrimination.
Pro-government youths gathered in a public plaza to read aloud the Universal Declaration of Human Rights; they held up black-and-white portraits honoring victims of terrorism in Cuba.
Precinct captains became angry when the president of the district's election bureau refused to pay them; a shot was fired in the air and the workers dispersed, tipping over and spilling ballots.
Civilians fired shots in the air and smashed rocks into a vehicle carrying people from Doctors Without Borders and at an Oxfam truck and stole bottled water.
About 12,000 people climb to the top of a volcano and link hands on a giant heart banner in order to draw attention to domestic violence.
Truckers blocked a crossing at Haiti's Malpasse border with the Dominican Republic to protest a Dominican tax on merchandise to and from Haiti.
Protesters were calling for better treatment of Haitians living in the Dominican republic after racial and human rights violations against them in the Dominican Republic.
150 demonstrators rioted, burned a makeshift dominican flag and tore down a sign at the Dominican embassy to protest the killing of a Haitian in the Dominican Republic.
Citizens demonstrated to protest increases in telephone costs and government austerity measures, police responded with tear gas and rubber bullets.
Fight broke out after journalist asked member of Cuban delegation when free elections would be held.
There was no reason provided for the attack.

Poet-turned-activist Javier Sicilia leads a caravan of demonstrators from Cuernavaca to Juarez to demand an end to drug-related violence.  After rallying in Juarez, the demonstrators cross into Texas.
7 killed in shootouts involving gangs in two neighborhoods.
Pirates attack and rob a sailboat.  The tourists are rescued by ham radio operators.
Attacker threw a Molotov cocktail at the home of EU agriculture consultant Pierre-Yves Baulain; the explosion did not cause any damage.
About 2,000 students who failed their high school exams and who were angry about fraud in the grading system ransacked the Education Ministry.

Hundreds of high school students protested and hurled rocks at the Education ministry building to demand that their schools be cleared of homeless people so that classes can resume and police fired tear gas.
Villagers pelt the president of congress (and former dictator) with rocks.
Hundreds of people opposed to the presidential candidacy of former dictator Efrain Rios Montt stage a march.
Montt was accused of genocidal actions against indigenous Guatemalans and protesters were present at his trial.
Miners were calling for reemployment of fired employees.
Miners continued to strike for the reinstatement of laid off employees.

target: Embassies of Germany, France, Spain, UK
issuenote: Members of unions demonstrated outside European embassies to protest EU proposal to cut sugar subsidies.
Nearly two dozen gas stations close to protest escalating violence.
Protesters were at the flight carrying Casanova from the United States where he had been living since retirement to El Salvador after his deportation from the U.S.
Fidel Castro led a march of several hundred thousand people protesting against  EU reprisals for Castro's crackdown on opponents.
