Gunmen hold up a bus full of French and Belgian tourists.
A tourist bus is ambushed and robbed.  Two European tourists are murdered.
3 killed, gunmen may have been looking for rifles that were supposed to be returned prior to recent election.
Police shot and killed 3 men who were suspected of robberies, witnesses describe as execution.

30 protesters led by a former union leader storm the office of a Mexican newspaper and scuffle with security guards.  The protest is designed to frighten away investors interested in buying the paper.
UNAM student radicals, holdouts from the April 1999 strike, scuffle with faculty.
Mexican police find a family of eight stabbed to death.  It is eventually learned that the murders were over a $115 debt that the father couldn't repay.
Farmers were protesting low wages.
Farmers demanded better pay.
Peasants occupy farmland, claiming it is being sold to outside parties.  In November, police forces evict the peasants in a violent battle.
Gunfire wounded three men when about 60 people shot their way into a farm whose owners retook it by force.
Protesters riot against a planned expropriation of land for a new hydroelectric dam.  Police respond with tear gas.
PRI supporters riot after a court decision giving the mayoral race to an opposition party.  They loot the town hall.
A group of leftists waits for conservative candidate Felipe Calderon outside a meeting with trade unions, screaming insults at him and slamming their fists against his car as he leaves.
About 30 Lopez Obrador supporters throw eggs at Felipe Calderon's car in Torreon.
Bank workers went on strike to demand better salaries and benefits.
A food convoy was attacked by men armed with picks and machetes and led to the hospitalization of six drivers.

Armed group of about 20 men blockaded a street and attacked a food convoy and peacekeepers fired warning shots into the air to scare them off; Haitian police arrested 14 people suspected of participating in the attack.
A U.N. food convoy traveling from Gonaives to Dessalines was stopped and overrun by people, who looted two trucks before peacekeepers regained control.
45 people, including two Haitian soldiers, looted a food depot and were arrested.
A near riot occurred at a food distribution center, with police lashing people with belts and switches as they struggled to get into the building for a handout.
A food storage depot was looted and burned down.
A mob ambushed a truck carrying emergency food.

Crowds of hungry residents followed food trucks, and one woman was trampled; shots were fired in the air by rebels to prevent the crowds from attacking the trucks; the next day, people looted food aid from rebel storage units.
About 2,000 people looted a warehouse of sugar, rice and condensed milk.
About 2,000 people mobbed a warehouse where U.S. troops were handing out sugar and other dry goods; one soldier fired a warning shot in the air while others tried to force people to form lines.
Hundreds of people looting a food warehouse owned by a businessman with army connections was fired on by a private security guard, injuring seven.
A young man was killed when security guards fired on a mob of people that stormed a food warehouse and the mob ransacked the precinct police station.
Hundreds of Haitians ransacked food warehouses; riot police fired tear gas and shots into the air.
A worker strike occurs at a Ford plant.
Around 2100 workers strike for higher wages.
Around 2100 workers strike for higher wages.
PRI supporters protest to demand that foreign human rights workers be expelled from Chiapas.
Armed students take over the foreign ministry and hold the Peruvian and Pakistani ambassadors hostage in protest of a forthcoming visit by the Pope.
A criminal gang robs a bus full of tourists.
A protest was held against foreign troops on the ground in Haiti.
Gunmen open fire on a retired general who helped negotiate the end of the civil war.  In a separate attack, his daughter is also targeted.  One civilian dies in the crossfire.
About 500 demonstrators blocked the arrival of a French ship carrying humanitarian aid because France was one of the primary supporters of the worldwide oil embargo on Haiti.
People were demonstrating against Hollande's visit to Haiti.
A French food convoy was attacked and looted.
Gunmen fired on a hospital as a delegation of high-ranking French officials were inside, a gun battle ensued in which one of the gunmen was killed and 2 others wounded.
A protest of 100 to 400 people took place as a senior French government official arrived at the hospital.
Workers went on strike to protest treatment by managers at plants.
Workers went on strike to protest treatment by managers at plants.

target: Front for the Advancement and Progress of  Haiti members
issuenote: Vigilantes went from house to house looking for FRAPH members, found a member's house and bloodied his wife's face, then killed a man with a machete outside, then went back to the FRAPH member's house and killed him.

target: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: A mob of people hacked off the arms of Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti member Paul Issa and set him afire, and stoned one of the front's leaders to death, Emmanuel Constant.
Residents blocked roads with stones and debris to protest gang attack associated with PNP.
Security forces exchanged gunfire with gangs during attempts to quell gang violence, later spread elsewhere as demonstrations and riots.
Security forces exchanged gunfire with gangs during attempts to quell gang violence, later spread elsewhere as demonstrations and riots.
Security forces exchanged gunfire with gangs during attempts to quell gang violence, later spread elsewhere as demonstrations and riots.
Security forces exchanged gunfire with gangs during attempts to quell gang violence, later spread elsewhere as demonstrations and riots.
The bus drivers were protesting violence from gangs targeting buses and bus drivers.
Demonstrators demanding jobs damaged a van and blocked a road with debris during protests outside a gas plant.
Hundreds of protesters blocked a road with tree trunks to demand construction jobs; three people were arrested over the weekend for blocking the gate of the Atlantic LNG plant.
Gunmen fired on a gay festival for unspecified reasons.
Greenpeace floats a hot-air balloon over Mexico City in a anti-genetically modified food campaign.
Members of Greenpeace protest against genetically modified corn.
Gunmen set house ablaze using Molotov cocktails, firing upon them as they attempted escape. Family of 4 killed.
Hundreds of people descended on the main port and looted beer, boxes of chicken parts, pork loins and jet skis; fights then broke out between the looters and at least one was wounded.
A group of several dozen demonstrators interrupts a cathedral Mass, chanting against the governor of Oaxaca, whom they accuse of repressing protesters in that state.
Tens of thousands march to the center of Oaxaca, accusing the governor of the state of corruption, violating human rights, and stealing an election.
Protesters demanding the governor's resignation march through the city.
Thousands of people take to the streets to demand the governor's resignation and briefly take two men hostage.
Several hundred people pillaged a grocery store.
About 100 workers staged a strike to demand higher wages and health benefits.
Miners stage a six week strike against a copper mining concern with facilities across the nation.
Miners strike to demand a profit-sharing agreement and other benefits.
Workers at Mexico's biggest copper mine strike, charging that Grupo Mexico hasn't paid them the equivalent of 5 percent of its equity in a deal that was promised 15 years prior.
Miners strike for  three years to demand safer working conditions.
Workers at Mexico's largest copper mine strike to demand better safety conditions.  Police and miners clash in January after the strike is declared illegal.
Miners at the La Caridad copper mine strike over a contract revision; they are joined on June 2 by miners at the Cananea mine.
Miners at the La Caridad copper mine strike over a contract revision; they are joined on June 2 by miners at the Cananea mine.
About 6000 Panama Canal workers strike to demand higher wages.
Workers expanding the Panama Canal are on strike demanding higher wages.
Workers expanding the Panama Canal are on strike demanding higher wages.
Workers expanding the canal protested against unsafe working conditions.
The PRI bows to charges of electoral fraud and turns over the governorship of Guanajuato state over to the PAN.  Hundreds of enraged PRI supporters storm the governor's palace.

25,000 members of Antorcha, a radical peasant organization affiliated with the PRI, camp out in front of the governor's office to demand 200 plots of land they claim were promised to them in a recent election campaign.
Farmers smash one million eggs to protest unfair egg competition from Guatemala and El Salvador.
Gunmen hold up a truck and make off with $8 million.
Electrical workers strike to renegotiate their contracts.
An anthropologist (Myrna Mack) is assassinated after issuing a report critical of the government's human rights record.
Mexican police turn over a Guatamalan migrant accused of robbery to a mob for $40.  The mob then beats the migrant to death.
The gang killed the civilians as a message to a rival gang.
2000 members of the PRI protest against alleged electoral fraud in Gerrero state, alleging that two mayors of the leftist PRD assumed office by fraud.  The protesters seize government buildings.
2000 members of the PRI protest against alleged electoral fraud in Gerrero state, alleging that two mayors of the leftist PRD assumed office by fraud.  The protesters seize government buildings.
Group fired on hotel from a boat in campaign to cripple tourism industry.
Residents blocked roads and burned debris to protest killing of bystander.

target: Gunmen from Wildman Street neighborhood (People's National Party stronghold)
issuenote: Gunmen from neighborhoods supporting opposition and ruling party engaged in shootout.
Scores of angry residents blocked a main street to protest the killing of 3 and injuring of another the previous night.
Hundreds rioted to protest killing of car wash owner.
Prisoners angry about delays in the judicial process threw rocks and set fires, with at least 6 prisoners being injured.
Truckers block the main route into Haiti to protest an increase in attacks on truckers in the Haitian capital.
A hand-grenade was thrown at the home of senior Haitian electoral official Carlo Dupiton, causing slight damage to the building.
Dominicans went on rampage, setting fires that destroyed homes. Two Haitians beheaded.
Villagers set fire to shacks occupied by Haitians in reprisal for death of businessman.
Dominican mobs torched Haitian homes over report that Haitian sexually assaulted a toddler.
200 Protestants take 3 state officials hostage to demand that they negotiate an end to an ongoing religious dispute with Catholics in a neighboring town.
Three protesters were killed by police over the Hidro Santa Rita project seen as a threat to the environment, and police officials were arrested and are being tried as of 6-May-15.
A British man and his Haitian partner are attacked by dozens of locals, who throw molotov cocktails and rocks at the couple's engagement ceremony.
Coast guard fired upon fishing boat, captain killed.
Armed men attack a train carrying Honduran migrants.  The attackers demand money and attack with machetes and guns.
Supporters of Hope blocked roads and burnt courthouse in protest of his killing, 1 killed during event.
Aristide militants stormed the Adventist Hospital three times during the night, stealing money and medicine.
Bombs were exploded at two top Havana hotels, Cuban government claims U.S. involvement and attempt to undermine tourism. Alpha 66 had contact with those responsible for attacks.
The offices of the country's human rights defense committee (a government agency) is bombed.
A worker for the government's human rights prosecutor is assassinated.
Unknown parties raid the offices of the country's chief human rights prosecutor, leaving it robbed, searched and smeared with excrement.
Members of the Central American Salvatrucha gang attack a train full of illegal immigrants and rob them.
Gunmen slaughter a family of Indian farmers in a land dispute.
Sectarian violence erupts between Indian coverts to evangelical Protestantism and a traditional Indian form of Catholicism.
Two Indian peasants who seized land after the Chiapas uprising are killed.
Two Catholics are killed in bout of religious violence.

target: Indians from the Center for Farmers and Farm Workers (CIOAC)
issuenote: Members of a farm group are shot dead in a confrontation over a land dispute with masked assailants.
Miners at the Naica lead mine strike for a wage hike.
Gunmen robbed workers at estate, possibly in response to efforts to dismantle gangs.
Gunmen fired at Campbell during a campaign stop in Hermitage community, traditionally loyal to Labour Party.
Opposition party stages several weeks of protests against election fraud.  On 12/13/1990, the protest escalates into a bloody clash with riot police.
PAN and PRD demonstrators accuse the PRI of fraud in the recent midterm elections.
PAN and PRD demonstrators accuse the PRI of fraud in the recent midterm elections.
20,000 marchers flood into Mexico City streets to protest against alleged fraud in municipal elections.
Nearly daily protests occur in Mexico City's central Zocalo plaza as poor farmers demonstrate against economic reforms.
PAN supporters accuse the PRI of electoral fraud in state elections.  They protest and burn down the state electoral commission office.  Police respond with tear gas and beatings.
Merchants in downtown Kingston staged two-day strike prompted by killing of businessman, protesting crime in area.
Hotel workers strike for a wage hike and stage a sit in at a set of hotels designated to host a meeting of foreign ministers.

Migrant workers employed in the US during the 1940s to the 1960s protest at the Interior Department to demand compensation for funds withheld from their paychecks.  The protest escalates; windows are broken and arrests are made.
Demonstators gather outside the Interior Department to protest the killing of a female protester just a few days prior.  The demonstrators briefly scuffle with police.
Education students confront the Interior Minister to demand a reopening of a dialogue on reforms to the national curriculum.  Police crack down with tear gas.
Four Interior Ministry employees were killed after armed men ambushed their vehicle as they were leaving the town of Belladere after swearing-in a new mayor.

target: International Civilian Mission in Haiti member
issuenote: A member of the International Civilian Mission in Haiti (MICIVIH) was shot in the head and killed.
Protesters gather outside the Israeli embassy to demonstrate against the war in Lebanon.
200 people protest outside the Israeli embassy over Israel's attacks on the Gaza Strip.
A group called F-26 protests outside the Italian embassy to demonstrate against the death of an Italian protester at the hands of police during a G-8 meeting in Genoa.
A handful of protesters were yelling outside Baby Doc's funeral procession denouncing him and his rule.
Rural police wielding guns and machetes arrested and threatened to kill journalists investigating the razing of 120 homes in a northern village.
A mob beats journalists during a campaign rally for Efrain Rios Montt.
Protesters were demonstrating against a Social Security fraud in which marked-up goods and sent money to the National Party.
Protesters were demonstrating against a Social Security fraud in which marked-up goods and sent money to the National Party.
Protesters were demonstrating against a Social Security fraud in which marked-up goods and sent money to the National Party.
Protesters were demonstrating against a Social Security fraud in which marked-up goods and sent money to the National Party.
Protesters were demonstrating against a Social Security fraud in which marked-up goods and sent money to the National Party.
Protesters were calling for the president's removal from office following a social security fraud scandal.
Protesters were calling for the president's resignation because of the social security scandal.
Protesters were calling for the president's resignation because of the social security scandal.
Protesters were trying to get into the presidential palace in protest of the social security fraud.
Students were protesting the presidential involvement in the social security fraud.

Members of the group Popular Organizations, supportive of a senator suspected in the case of slain Haitian journalist Jean Dominique, threw stones and ignited tires to protest against the judge who was heading the case.
Lawyers across Haiti staged a one-day strike to protest against what they say is a corrupt and ineffective judicial system.

50 protesters staged a sit-in in front of the Justice Ministry to criticize a judge's decision that recommended former dictator Duvalier face trial for alleged financial crimes but not for more serious human rights abuses.
A demonstration was called to protest the Justice Minister's loyalty to past military-backed governments.
Protesters rally against the abduction of children and demand increased safety measures in their neighborhood.  The protestors take overbuses and block roads.  Police make arrests.
Thousands of people across Honduras protest a wave of journalist killings.
The two groups entered a gun fight for no reported reason
Although there was no clear issue, this is a supposed cartel related incident.
Three men raid the office of a gay rights organization and beat two of its members.
Local authorities organize a march to show support for a La Familia cartel leader slain by police.
The former mayor of El Ayote shoots reporter Maria Jose Bravo in a row over local election results outside a vote-counting center.

Clashes broke out after a county sheriff and his deputies attempted to evict peasants occupying disputed land; the two deputies and one peasant were killed in an initial confrontation and 12 people were killed total.

About 70 gunmen loyal to a local faction of the PRI descend upon an Indian village, massacring Tzotzil Indians and members of an EZLN affiliated group called Las Abejas.  Many of the killers were political rivals.

About 70 gunmen loyal to a local faction of the PRI descend upon an Indian village, massacring Tzotzil Indians and members of an EZLN affiliated group called Las Abejas.  Many of the killers were political rivals.

target: Lavalas Party member Joseph Zeus Duverge
issuenote: Opposition partisans took a machete to a Lavalas Party member Joseph Zeus Duverge.
Dozens of people from the Lebanese immigrant community march to the Lebanese embassy to protest against the Israeli-Lebanon war.
Legislators Jean Mandenave and Kerset Charles Jean-Phillipe were attacked by gunmen while their vehicle was stopped in traffic.

Hundreds of enraged government employees set upon lawmakers with rocks and clubs as they leave the National Assembly just minutes after passing a law allowing the firing of public workers who support a coup.

target: Lenford Harvey - gay man who counsels people with AIDS
issuenote: Harvey was abducted from home and found dead the next day.
Two men shot execution style, allegedly because they had switched loyalty from PNP to JLP.
Gunmen open fire on Liberal party headquarters in advance of an election.
The leader of the National Party leads a protest, refusing to recognize the election victory of the Liberal Party.
Protesters block a highway to demand the ouster of a town mayor accused of embezzlement.
Residents protest the actions of a local mayor by seizing ballot boxes during a state election and burning them.
Gustavo Guerrero, a farmer, sets himself on fire to protest local authorities, who had prevented him from selling melons in the main square.
Looting occurred in aftermath of Hurricane Ivan, armed men roamed streets and ransacked business, exchanged fire with police.
Looting occurred in aftermath of Hurricane Ivan, armed men roamed streets and ransacked business, exchanged fire with police.
Looting occurred in aftermath of Hurricane Ivan, armed men roamed streets and ransacked business, exchanged fire with police.
Protesters clashed with police to prevent the seating of a local elections board.

target: Local electoral official Carl Henry Emilicar
issuenote: A local electoral official, Carl Henry Emilicar, was wounded by unidentified gunmen who fired on him as he rode in his car.
Residents set up flaming roadblocks in response to killing of local gang leader.
Masked members of the EPR shoot up the construction site of a jail.  Spray painted demands are left behind, demanding the release of political prisoners.
A crowd accuses the mayor of a small town of bringing people from El Salvador to cast votes in his favor.  They riot, setting a voting booth on fire.  Police disperse them with tear gas.
Attackers burst into the home of a local opposition campaign director and hacked him to death with machetes, cutting off his head.
About 50 local environmentalists repeatedly block a road so that logging trucks can't pass.  The government sends in the army to quell the dispute.
A pro-Aristide crowd rioted.
700 citizens occupied an oil tanker in effort to flee to U.S., takeover ended when all left ship voluntarily.
Policemen fired warning shots when voters began angrily accusing a man of ballot stuffing; he was arrested and no one was injured.
Protesters rally outside the headquarters of Noriega's political party on the anniversary of the American invasion, where they burn him in effigy.
The Association of Urban Transport staged a strike against street gangs.
Gang violence caused these deaths.
Protesters charge a mayor with abuse of power, nepotism, and sexual harassment, forcing him to quit and flee the town.
Assailants kill a mayor and another man in a dispute motivated by a disagreement over a mine.
A mayor is handing out campaign fliers when he is killed in a drive by shooting.
A demonstration was held against Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
Disgruntled city workers protest to demand the mayor's reinstatement.  The protests lead to the mayor's dismissal.
The mayor of Jalapa is assassinated a week ahead of elections.
400 farmers march in their underwear to demand that the mayor return a parcel of land they claim City Hall took from them.  They end their protest by stripping off al their clothes.
Supporters of losing mayor Georges Simon ransacked a community radio station and the home of its owner and also set fire to the house of Mayor-elect Belcombe and wounded 12 people.
An anti-government demonstration escalated to anti-government violence.
Explosion occurred at Havana's Melia-Cohiba Hotel, government claims bombing was attempt to undermine tourism and that U.S. was involved. Alpha 66 had contact with those responsible.
Supporter of Balaguer fatally shot member of Social Democratic Party during a political argument.
Housewives strike to draw attention to the fact that housework benefits society as a whole.  This forces some husbands to do housework for the first time in their lives.

Members of the SITRASE truckers union blockade the site of new airport construction with their big rigs.  The incident grows out of an ongoing dispute between two unions, SITRASE and the Mexican Confederation of Workers, over jobs at the site.
Between 150 and 250 thugs enter a Ford factory, firing guns and beating workers. The rank and file are disgruntled over closed negotiations between the union and Ford.
Independent unions staged a demonstration and rioting occurred.
Protesters were calling for President Michel Martelly to step down because he has not addressed hunger and they were also protesting that elections were overdue.
Violent protesters were demonstrating against President Michel Martelly, calling for his resignation for corruption and delayed elections.
Violent protesters were demonstrating against President Michel Martelly, calling for his resignation for corruption and delayed elections.
Protesters want the President and Prime Minister to step down and for the government to hold new elections, which have been delayed for three years.
The central government announced that three-year-delayed elections have been delayed again.
The central government announced that three-year-delayed elections have been delayed again.
Protesters were calling for the President's and Vice-President's resignation because of three-year election delays.
Protesters were calling Martelly a dictator and protesting delayed elections.
Protesters were demonstrating against the president, saying he allowed elections to pass without calling new ones.

target: Ministry of Justice and Public Safety
issuenote: Leaders of the Mara Salvatrucha and Barrio 18 gangs are staging hunger strikes to protest conditions in the Zacatecoluca prison.
The army repulses a rebel attack on a Miskito village.
A violent highway robbery occurs -- a gunman shoots and wound an American missionary couple.
Individuals Tending Toward the Savage attacked the Monterrey Technological Institute due to environmental concerns.
Hundreds of teaching students from 15 colleges demonstrate in Amalcingo.  A small group of students storm the Morelos state legislature and hold deputies hostage for 15 hours.
Hundreds of teaching students from 15 colleges demonstrate in Amalcingo.  A small group of students storm the Morelos state legislature and hold deputies hostage for 15 hours.
A lone kidnapper abducts two Mormon missionaries for 7.5 hours.  The kidnapper is arrested.
Men with automatic weapons hijack a bus full of Mormon tourists from the US.  The men rob the bus, killing one of the tourists.

Homeless people demonstrated by blocking access to municipal garbage dumps in a protest over recycling rights. Garbage men often claim items in the trash and recycle them, putting them at odds with the homeless.

A woman protests in front of the governor's office to demand justice for the killing of her teenage daughter after a judge exonerates the main suspect.  Gunmen then drive up in a car and shoot her dead.
El Barzon organizes protesters, who ride horses from Cuidad Juarez to Mexico City to protest against NAFTA's farm policies.
Farm activists stage a 36 hour blockade of the international border to protest unrestricted corn imports from the US, as established under the terms of NAFTA.
Hundreds of applicants rejected from National Autonomous University stage a building occupation.

Radical students and their supporters burst into the offices of the university disciplinary board and steal student records in an effort to avoid expulsion.  After the attack, about 50 other people block traffic to demonstrate.
Poor farmers seize a union building to express discontent with new economic reforms.
Public sector doctors strike against the national health system to demand higher wages.  The doctors later clash with police.
More than 1000 angry Indians surround a team from the federal Rights Commission, which had come to investigate the June 10 raid on the town.
Migrants were protesting human rights violations against them.
Demonstrators briefly interrupt a session of the legislature to protest CAFTA.
2000 workers at water utility went on strike to demand higher wages, leaving much of the island without water.
Dozens of cowboy-hatted farmers protest outside Nestle offices, saying current trade policies hurt Mexican coffee growers.

Five gunmen storm the Nicaraguan embassy to protest President Violeta Chamorro's policy of allowing Sandinistas to control the police and the military as part of that country's post-war settlement. Nicaragua eventually pays the gunmen to leave.
A terrorist group bombs the offices of a business federation during the funeral of a businessman who was murdered.  The group demands that Spanish investigators of the crime leave the country.
Workers strike for three days to demand higher wages at a Nissan plant.
1700 unionized workers strike to demand higher wages.
Radial teachers were protesting the education exams teachers are required to take.
A human rights activist is killed by unknown gunmen.
A mob of unionists blockades a newspaper in a labor dispute, trapping journalists and other employees inside for over a month.  In July, the unionists attack the building, forcing their way inside.
Hundreds demonstrate against the local governments, blaming them for the rising drug violence.

About 150 Haitians took part in a demonstration against an international embargo aimed at returning to office Haiti's democratically-elected president; the demonstrators attacked youths who taunted them.
2,500 demonstrators massed at the Port-au-Prince airport to protest a trade and diplomatic embargo the OAS put on Haiti.
Several hundred protesters demonstrated at the Port-au-Prince airport to protest a trade and diplomatic embargo the OAS put on Haiti.
Several thousand people demonstrated at the airport to protest the OAS embargo and the possible return of Aristide.
Members of the Haitian Association of Youths for People Power staged a hunger strike to protest the OAS embargo.
4 men killed while at a home, breaking peace between 2 gangs.
Supporters and opponents of Castro engaged in physical struggle during novelist's speech criticizing Castro.
Opponents of a candidate for president of the Confederation of Mexican Workers protest outside a union meeting and then force their way inside.
Gunmen fired on 500-car motorcade of Seaga while on campaign tour.
About 100 Protesters angry over the killing of a Haitian journalist razed the headquarters of the Space for Concord and stoned the offices of the Struggling People's Organization.
About 100 Aristide supporters demonstrated outside the U.S. embassy to denounce what they called OAS meddling in Haitian affairs.
Aristide supporters disrupted a peaceful opposition demonstration in front of OAS headquarters.

target: Organization of the People in Struggle
issuenote: 200 Aristide supporters opened fire on the office of the Organization of the People in Struggle and threw firebombs at the building and fired at a school, demanding the arrest of Gerard Gourgue, and one was shot and killed by police.

Via social media, protesters called for business leaders, churches, farmers, students, indigenous peoples, and other groups to protest for the removal of the President regarding the customs bribery ring.
Protesters were calling for the removal of President Otto Perez due to the graft scandal.
Protesters were demonstrating in front of the Supreme Court as the courts were holding a hearing against ex-president Otto Perez in his corruption scandal.
PAN and PRI supporters protest against one another over a disputed election in Juarez.  Masked gunmen attack the rallies, gunning down two men in a parking lot in broad daylight.

Student PRI supporters seize control of a building at the Hermanos Escobar Agricultural College. PAN and PRD students march on the building and the situation escalates to rioting.  Police respond by storming the college.
Opposition activists threw rocks at motorcade carrying PM and other PNP candidates.

Thousands of PRI supporters block highways to protest reports that their governor was being forced to resign in favor of a candidate from the PRD, claiming it was their candidate who won an election. The protests escalate to rioting.

Hundreds of PRI supporters attack a PRD rally; specifically, the attackers are supporters of Jose Hernandez of the PRI, who has a long running dispute with a recently deceased PRD candidate.  Clashes last for several hours.

Peasants storm the PRI headquarters after the party's electoral loss; they demand that the party pay more attention to grassroots organizations like theirs and that a jailed leader be freed from prison.
About 50 farmers clash with private security guards outside the PRI headquarters to demand the release of a man arrested for squatting on public land.
Thousands of college age demonstrators march to protest against a possible return to power of the PRI in the upcoming election.

Tens of thousands of university students march to protest against a possible return to power by the PRI in the upcoming elections.  They also rally against media coverage of the election, which they say is biased.
Tens of thousands of demonstrators march to protest the likely return to power of the PRI in the upcoming election.
Thousands of anti-PRI protesters demonstrate against the return of the PRI to power in the upcoming election.
Tens of thousands of protesters march, accusing the PRI and the president-elect of vote buying and corruption.
Thousands march to protest alleged vote buying by the president-elect and the PRI.
Around 500 protesters clash with police over the PRI's recent election victory.
PRI and PRD legislators brawl in the Tabasco state legislature over the naming of an interim governor after an October gubernatorial election is annulled.
Bus owners strike to protest a court decision blocking public transport fare increases needed to make improvements to vehicles.
Students protest a proposed budget cut at the university.
On an election runoff day, a man was killed in a fight between partisans.
Supporters of a rebel wanted for homicide burned tires and threw rocks at passers-by.
Militants also used guns and stones to stop cars and loot them of handbags, luggage and cell phones.
Taylor attacked pastor with machete, later tried to attack police and was shot and killed.
About 1,000 Aristide supporters broke into the headquarters of the Patriotic Action Committee, injuring four people and sacking the building.
Unknown assailants shot at a soldier guarding the U.N.'s new headquarters; he escaped injury because the bullets hit him in his helmet and vest.
A UN peacekeeper from the Philippines was shot in the head and killed when an unknown number of armed gunmen opened fire.
A Jordanian peacekeeper was shot and killed while on patrol.

A UN peacekeeper was dragged from a car and shot and peacekeepers fired tear gas and shots to disperse a crowd before recovering the body and two men were detained and several market stalls were set on fire.
A crowd of people at a food distribution site threw rocks at peacekeepers, and the peacekeepers fired tear gas into the crowd.
Dozens of young men burned tires and threw rocks at peacekeepers, accusing them of standing by while Haitian police shot and killed two men.
Residents stoned a U.N. vehicle and fired on them, slightly wounding two and other peacekeepers were also shot at and injured.
Peacekeepers raiding a police station held by former soldiers were fired on and fired back; one peacekeeper and two former soldiers were killed; in another incident, a peacekeeper was killed.
Peacekeepers raiding a police station held by former soldiers were fired on and fired back; one peacekeeper and two former soldiers were killed; in another incident, a peacekeeper was killed.
A pro-Aristide gang clashed with peacekeepers, and a young bystander was killed.
Gunmen opened fire on U.N. troops at a checkpoint, wounding two peacekeepers and two Haitian Red Cross workers.
Peruvian U.N. soldiers were patrolling in an armored vehicle when they came under fire from armed gunmen; two peacekeepers were injured in the attack.
Gang members attacked a U.N. military position, and peacekeepers fired back, killing one gang member.
Armed groups using children as human shields fired at UN troops; over a period of three days of shooting, one UN soldier was injured.
Gumen shot and killed two peacekeepers and seriously wounded another at a security checkpoint.
Hundreds of people marched past a U.N. fort and made obscene gestures at Jordanian peacekeepers after two people were allegedly shot by peacekeepers earlier that day.
Gang members fired on a UN security checkpoint and exchanged gunfire; one youth was injured.
An armed Haitian gang exchanged gunfire with peacekeepers, with three peacekeepers being injured and at least one gang member being shot and killed over three days.
Over three days of gunfire exchanged between armed groups and peacekeepers after armed groups attacked UN security stations; 8 armed group members were killed.
Five gang members were killed in an exchangeof gunfire with UN peacekeepers.
Peacekeepers trying to remove debris from a road were fired on and fired back in self-defense; residents then threw rocks at peacekeepers and accused them of opening fire and killing two.
Two Jordanian peacekeepers were shot and killed when they came under attack by gunmen.
Clashes between armed gangs and peacekeepers led to the deaths of four gang members and several others were injured.
At least two peacekeepers were injured in exchanges with armed gangs and one passerby was killed in the cross-fire.
Hundreds of people protested against peacekeepers from Nepal, blaming them for the cholera epidemic and demanding they leave the country.

target: Peasant Organization of the Southern Sierra (OCSS)
issuenote: Farmers on their way to an OCSS protest to march against police brutality are shot dead by police.  The EPR is formed in response to this event.
Two peasant groups clash in a dispute over farmland.
15 masked gunmen kill four members of a peasant family and then steal their mule and other possessions.
A hand grenade explodes during the robbery of a truck carrying peasants.
10 men piled out of a vehicle and - brandishing weapons and throwing stones - ordered pedestrians off the streets; this was seen as an attempt to keep people from participating in upcoming elections.
Suspected gang members robbed Ferriz for no reported reason.
Fishermen in Salina Cruz block the entrance to a refinery to protest against environmental damage.
Landowners on the island protested the development of resort that would be built on flamingo habitat.
A Pentecostal pastor is shot dead in an apparent incident of religiously motivated violence.
Office of the ruling party was firebombed in St. Ann Parish.
A PNP worker and two other people were killed during election violence.
Demonstrators were celebrating the detainment of Baldetti and called for Perez Molina's resignation.
Farmers block access to oil fields and a petrochemical plant to demand compensation for damaged coconut crops.
At least 300 residents of two communities affected by a 2004 oil spill prevent employees of Pemex from heading to work.
Crew of Panamanian cargo ship on hunger strike to protest law firms preventing their departure.
Gunmen raid a pharmaceutical lab, killing four security guards and stealing about a ton of ephedrine.
46 tug boat workers staged a four-day strike at a plant to address safety concerns and worker wages.
8000 people gather to protest against violence in Juarez since the July 4 death of an area drug lord.
About 20 armed men raided a polling booth.
Gunmen fired into the air and attempted to steal ballot box, one man stabbed.
Armed groups of Mejia supporters surrounded polling places, threatening to take ballot boxes.
More than 100 disgruntled voters protested, closing down some polling stations that were open.
A group of voters, angry that some voting stations had not opened by 4 p.m., set tires ablaze in a failed attempt to block a road.
Youths attacked a polling station and scattered thousands of ballots.
Men took over a polling station and commandeered ballot boxes, stuffing them with marked ballots.
Shots fired at polling station and police in same voting district on election day.
Two polling stations were set on fire.
Hundreds of protesters raided polling places and dumped ballots in the streets.
Two men and two women ride topless down the City's main boulevard to protest pollution and to encourage people to use bicycles instead of cars.
Workers building cruise ship port walked off job, claiming they were underpaid and overtaxed.
Aristide supporters looted Port-Au-Prince's warehouses.

20 armed individuals showed up to an outdoor market to protest efforts by the Port-au-Prince mayor's office to sack the market's director and battled to control its lucrative trade, injuring five people; four suspects were arrested.
A shooting occurred at City Hall in an apparent attempt to scare the outspoken mayor of Port-Au-Prince from campaigning for president.
1000 coffee workers driven from their farms and jobs by falling prices set up protest camps outside the president's residence and the national legislature.
Anti-government protesters clash with police and ruling party supporters outside of Congress as the president delivers his annual state of the nation speech.
5000 workers demonstrate against the president's economic policies.

Crowds march to demand the president's resignation after a video surfaces in which a lawyer accused the president of ordering his death just days before he was actually murdered.  Counter-protesters gather and jeer at the crowds.
50,000 people demand a better justice system, and call for the impeaching of the president.
Human rights activists, carrying placards accusing President Bush of racism and prejudice, tried to block the gangway of a Coast Guard cutter as it unloaded Haitians.
10,000 protesters march to demand the ouster of newly inaugurated president Ernesto Zedillo.  Some clash with riot police.
More than 4500 government workers protest the refusal of Mexico's president to hand out farewell bonuses at the end of his term.
The military forces the president out of office.

The president orders a referendum allowing him to seek another term.  Congress, the military, and the Supreme Court call this move illegal and threaten to remove him from office.  Thousands demonstrate, demanding the president leave.
The military ousts president Manual Zelaya.
A few hundred Aristide supporters marched to accuse President Martelly of abusing the country's Constitution, claiming he has dual nationality.
About 100 protesters demanded that President Martelly prove he's eligible for office.
The President and Vice President are under investigation for a customs bribery ring.
Protesters continued to call for the resignation of President Perez.
Political opponents demonstrate on the day of the newly elected president's inauguration over the country's involvement in Iraq.
Several thousand radical teachers belonging to dissident groups that oppose the official union leadership tear down police barricades in front of the president's residence, demanding higher wages.

To protest Congress' vote stripping Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador of his immunity from prosecution, PRD conduct several nationwide protests. Several stage hunger strikes outside the President's residence, while some attempt to invade his ranch.
Thousands of Obrador's supports protest and attempt to blockage the Congress in order to prevent the president from delivering an address.  They demand a vote recount for their candidate.
The president visits the scene of the battle in Esteli, and is greeted by angry protests.
Hundreds of truck drivers circle the office of the president with their rigs to demand lower diesel fuel prices.
Five women strip naked in the legislative building to demand the resignation of the president.  They also make reference to the murder of women in Ciudad Juarez.
A group of 20 people burst in the office of the UNAM university president, breaking windows and then occupying the Rector's Tower to protest the expulsion of five students.
More than 100 teachers march in protest a visit by Felipe Calderon, recently declared as victor in the presidential election.
Six gunmen attack the presidential guard as they draw their payroll from a bank.  The gunmen steal nearly $50,000 dollars after the brazen attack.
A presidential security guard and a candidate's secretary are shot and killed just weeks ahead of a runoff vote.
Hundreds of demonstrators called for Aristide to stay on and candidate Preval to withdraw from the race for President.
Gunmen fired on 500-car motorcade of Patterson while on campaign tour.
Residents protested hurricane damage tour of P.M., citing government failure to build retaining wall.
Guy Phillipe supporters demonstrated against Prime Minister Yvon Neptune.

Masked gunmen, alleged to be Maya Indians from Chamula, attack a prison, leading to a mass prison break and riot.  The Indians are in conflict with local authorities over the right to practice Evangelical Protestantism.
400 prison inmates stage a brief hunger strike to demand a fairer distribution of telephone and visiting hours.
Prisoners riot and take control of a prison.  They demand improved sanitary and living conditions, and an investigation into corruption at the prison.
Prisoners riot and take control of a prison.  They demand improved sanitary and living conditions, and an investigation into corruption at the prison.
Prisoners gangs riot over a lack of food and clean drinking water in the aftermath of Hurricane Mitch.
Prisoners riot to protest their living conditions.
Prisoners riot to protest their living conditions.
Hundreds of inmates begin a hunger strike to protest overcrowded, inhuman living conditions.
Prisoners riot to demand better food and living conditions.
100 prisoners demanding their freedom rioted in Haiti's main prison; there were gunshots and two people were killed and unveiled a banner demanding justice.
Prison inmates riot over living conditions.
Prison inmates riot over living conditions.
Inmates at a youth prison riot against living conditions.
Juvenile inmates riot twice in two days to demand better food.
A prison riot occurs over the poor treatment of inmates at the hands of the guards.
Prisoners stage a hunger strike to demand their release.  They go so far as to sew their own mouths shut.
Riot broke out between rivals groups of inmates, sparked by protests against overcrowded conditions.
A dozen inmates were injured after they rioted due to the subhuman conditions of their imprisonment.
Several dozen inmates set mattresses and other materials ablaze to protest the subhuman conditions of their imprisonment.
Prisoners riot in La Modelo jail after two of them are accused of abusing other inmates and stealing their food.
A riot occurs at a prison. The prisoners say they rioted because they were not given food or water since the previous riot. Police kill many prisoners while trying to regain control.
Workers demanding back wages were fired upon and youths stoned a police patrol; officers later returned to retrieve the truck and opened fire, killing one.
Striking teachers armed with pipes, wood planks, and clubs seize eight private radio states after unknown assailants shot up a government owned station already under the strikers' control.
Peasants stage a land invasion, taking over a ranch.
Public school students went to private schools to force them to close in support of striking public school teachers, some threw rocks and police fired tear gas.
Haitians beat up an army-linked gunman.
Supporters and opponents of a bill chant outside the Mexico City legislature as it passes a bill legalizing abortion.
A group of about 50 local Catholics with hunting rifles open fire on Protestant families as they take their children to school.
Rival groups of protesters clash over property claims.
About 5000 Zapatista rebels demonstrate to show their support for the protesters in Oaxaca, who took over the center of that city in a protest against the election of a governor.
An election bureau was raided, and the attackers were chased off before they could burn voting papers.
The Cannibal Army stole a tractor and crashed it through the wall of a provincial jail, freeing 159 prisoners in an effort to free a political activist, killing one.
Gangs are vying for involvement in the government Security Council.
Over 40,000 public hospitals workers strike for better wages.
3400 banana workers strike for higher wages.
Cuba's Revolutionary Sports Movement held a protest against Puerto Rico and the U.S.

About 300 residents protest against the radical leaders of the July 11, 2002 hostage crisis, demanding they be allowed to hold elections and regain a formal police force and government, both of which had been forced out of town.
Residents looted the Radio Africa station because it was pro-Aristide.
Armed ranch workers attack employees who were occupying the ranch land to demand payment for their work.
300 peasants armed with machetes and automatic rifles try to take over a ranch.
Two bombs exploded, killing a 7-year old girl and injuring two other people.

target: Random targets around Port-Au-Prince and Petionville
issuenote: Several spots in Port-Au-Prince as well as 3 spots in Petionville were hit by homemade bombs, killing one and injuring at least 14 others.

target: Random targets around Port-Au-Prince and Petionville
issuenote: Several spots in Port-Au-Prince as well as 3 spots in Petionville were hit by homemade bombs, killing one and injuring at least 14 others.

Health workers stage a sit-in at health department offices to protest an incident where a gang of armed men robbed and raped three nurses working for a vaccination team.  They also protest against the health department.
About 2,000 people rioted at a relief feeding center, fleeing when American military police drove up, then resumed the looting once the military left.
People looted a truckload of relief supplies and made off with mattresses, shovels, sacks of flour and boxes of medicine.
Unidentified gunmen fired at the home of Rene Theodore, who would be prime minister under a new government proposed by ousted President Aristide.
Pre-election violence in the slums.
Residents of Xochiltepec raid Las Huertas and kill one person as a result of an ongoing land dispute.
Residents of Teojomulco raid Santiago Xochiltepec in an ongoing land dispute, firing hundreds of shots at the village school.
Residents of rival communities clash.  Gunmen ambush a truckload of people on a mountain road, apparently as a result of a land dispute.
Unknown gunmen kill a local leader of a small political party, minutes after he voted.
Sandinista supporters protest, riot, and blockade the national legislature over opposition legislation that shortens the terms of some 25 top magistrates and civil servants.

target: Rival Indian groups aligned with the PRD
issuenote: Hundreds of Zapatistas protest the loss of water service after refusing to cooperate in maintaining and paying for the area's water system; the Zapatistas attend a protest against this but are then attacked by rival Indians as they leave.
A land dispute between farmers erupts in violence.  Residents of Santo Domingo Teojomulco open fire on farmers from a rival town, San Lorenzo Texmelucan.
Two gangs exchanged gunfire after arguing over a shipment of donated rice and flour, with three people being injured.
Shootout broke out between gangs, Labour Party member hit by stray bullet.
A three-car convoy of gunmen fired shots as part of gang feud, killing 2 and injuring 3.
Rival gangs shot at each other.
A battle for gang territory occurs.  14 are massacred on a football field.
At least two people were killed by gunfire when rival groups clashed.
A man and his 12 year old daughter attack and kill a neighboring land owner in a dispute.
Ruling party official killed rival in dispute over voting credentials.

Preval supporters smashed the windows of a vehicle carrying Union party supporter and a Haitian folk singer; police fired shots to disperse the crowd, beat attackers with rifle butts and detained several.
Rival prison gangs battle over living conditions.
Supporters of a victorious presidential candidate attack the losing candidate the day of the election.
Masked gunmen spray bullets at a Catholic bishop, an outspoken champion of poor Indians.  He escapes unhurt.

1000 teachers and parents pull children out of school to protest and deliver petitions to local officials decrying proposals to build a natural gas terminal in the town, which relies primarily upon Spring Break tourism.
A rural election bureau was attacked by right-wing extremists carrying machetes, clubs and stones and injured 10 people, including some political candidates.
Thousands of residents looted huge sacks of food and cement mix and also looted the U.N. World Food Program warehouse the next day.
Hundreds of looters tooks sacks of rice from Port-Au-Prince's industrial park.

target: Sam Tyson - chairman of the Sugar Producers' Federation
issuenote: 13,000 workers from Jamaica's nine sugar factories went on strike in search of better wages.

target: San Bartolome de los Llanos Alliance
issuenote: Two factions of Tzotzil Indians clash over land.

target: San Bartolome de los Llanos Alliance
issuenote: Members of feuding Tzotzil Indian groups clash.  Alliance members attack the walled compound of the House of the People.

target: San Bartolome de los Llanos Alliance
issuenote: Two factions of Tzotzil Indians clash over land at the edge of large sugar cane fields.  This is the 33rd murder in the feud between the two factions since 1968.

target: San Bartolome de los Llanos Alliance
issuenote: Rival peasants groups clash in a land dispute.  Members of a group affiliated with the PRI are ambushed by a leftist group called The House of the People.
Some 400 former Contras seize 41 pro-Sandinista legislators and soldiers, demanding that two Sandinista government officials resign.
Non-Sandinista cane cutters attempt to break into a sugar mill taken over by Sandinista workers.
Recontras open fire on a Sandinista cooperative farm.
Anti-Sandinista Miskitos take over public buildings.  The army is sent in to restore order.
Students take over two schools to protest a program that requires high school students to teach at least one person to read in order to graduate.
Protester gather to demonstrate against high electricity prices and education reform.  Police open fire on the protest.
Opponents of a mining project demonstrate.  Two mine security guards and a protester die during the riot.
The government military was trying for force the self-proclaimed defense forces to put down their weapons and disband.
The government military was trying for force the self-proclaimed defense forces to put down their weapons and disband.

Angry union members surround the Senate building and fight bloody battles with police to protest a pension reform bill.  The protesters engage in running battles and blockades that cut off traffic on dozens of streets.
Alburquerque fought with Sanz over Municipal League dispute, Bautista hit with shotgun pellets.
Looting ocurred at the Shell terminal in Bizoton and armed Aristide supporters looted food stores in the Martissant neighborhood of Port-Au-Prince.
Several hundred people pushed and shoved to break down the door of a U.N. shelter.
Hundreds of people looted TV sets, mattresses and sacks of flour from shipping containers.
A grenade explodes harmlessly at a shopping center on election day.
Looters with machetes struck numerous shops and World Food Program warehouses as well as an Eagle Wings Foundation distribution center of various goods.
2000 steelworkers strike to demand that alleged violations of their contract be settled and that seven fired workers be rehired.
Organized crime groups battle over territory inside a prison.
Gunmen shot and wounded prominent socialist Philippe Stevenson in what was seen as an attempt to intimidate his party from participating in upcoming elections.
One soldier was killed by a group armed with Uzi assault weapons; police blamed other soldiers for the attack.
200 people gather to protest at the town hall over the shooting death of four municipal workers by army soldiers.
Guerrillas ambush soldiers and police in an area wracked with land disputes.
Hundreds of fishermen protesting a new law that prohibits them from trawling for shrimp in a marine reserve form a human chain across a highway, leaving scores of American tourists stranded.
Seven men shouting pro-Aristide slogans brandished pistols, threw stones and tossed a Molotov cocktail that didn't explode at several members of an opposition political party.

target: Space for Concord opposition coalition opposition militant
issuenote: Space for Concord opposition coalition militant Alexandre Shelo was attacked and shot in the knee.

About 20 Mexican and Spanish citizens hold demonstrations in front of the Spanish Embassy during a visit by Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, decrying his support for American plans to attack Iraq.
Spaniards demonstrated outside embassy to protest Basque group ETA's killing of Spanish politician and presence of ETA leaders in D.R.
Workers' strike over delayed wage payment escalated into riot, worker shot security guard and 2 fellow workers.

About 180 students and Indian activists briefly take over the Spanish embassy, demanding to meet with officials from the president's office and demanding a say in who is named as head of the Indian development office.
Police try to clear a farm of 600 squatters, triggering a clash that leaves at least 12 dead.
Police chase 1500 squatters off of land in San Jose, including illegal Nicaraguan immigrants.  This causes a diplomatic incident.
Police evict squatters from land owned by the Standard Fruit Company, triggering riots.
Students protesting for an improved curriculum barricaded themselves inside an administration building and smashed car windows with rocks and police fired tear gas and made arrests.
Education students torched a U.N. vehicle and threw bottles and rocks at police to protest the removal of math and science classes from the teaching school's curriculum.
300 students protesting curriculum changes and demanding a raising of the minimum wage and also that U.N. forces leave Haiti threw rocks at police and set a car on fire; police fired tear gas.
Students protesting curriculum changes, the minimum wage and the U.N. presence in Haiti attacked and burned a U.N. police vehicle and peacekeepers fired tear gas.
Students protesting curriculum changes, the minimum wage and the U.N. presence in Haiti had tear gas thrown at them by police.

Student protesters demanding  a hike in Haiti's minimum wage, changes in curriculum and the departure of the U.N. troops clashed with police and police entered the medical school campus and arrested 20.
Villagers march to demand the release from prison of 87 Indians they say are falsely accused of participating in the 1997 Acteal Massacre.
Indian women march to protest the jailing of several Indian men.
Workers at four recently privatized steel mills strike for salary increases.
One person was killed in a clash between President Preval supporters and members of the Struggling People's Organization.
Sugar production workers striking to demand pay raises and benefits.
Thousands of sugar workers strike over salaries and retirement benefits.
Activists violently protest against an international economic summit, throwing rocks, sticks, signposts, and barricades.  Several international activists are arrested and deported.
Six people killed and others wounded in election day violence, including gunfight between party supporters in Barahona.
Six people killed and others wounded in election day violence, including gunfight between party supporters in Barahona.
Six people killed and others wounded in election day violence, including gunfight between party supporters in Barahona.
Violence occurs between two PRI factions.  A PRI activist who lost a recent mayoral election urges her supporters to attack loyalists of Chimalhuacan's new mayor.
Vehicles of PNP supporters (including gang members) were stoned, who then retaliated with attacks, 1 dead.
Citizens attacked opposition party supporters, killing 3.
Thousands of protesters surround the Supreme Court building to demand that the justices be removed from their posts for corruption.

Death Commando storm the Supreme Court and take several of the justices hostage, demanding money for a liver transplant.  Families of the hostages eventually raise money, and the gunmen are flown to Guatemala.

Students from all over the capital take to the streets to protest and riot against a Supreme Court ruling upholding a decision by the National Institute to expel five students for rowdy behavior.  Riot police use tear gas.
Police acted on an anonymous tip regarding the whereabouts of a suspected gang meeting, killing 8 people.
Police beat gay man, mob later stoned and stabbed him to death.
A mob lynches two suspected robbers.
Crowds fed up with rising crime lynched two suspected thieves.
The Military was trying to gain control over the state from "suspects" either vigilantes or gang members, it is unspecified.
A Swedish embassy guard is killed in a politically motivated attack.  Sweden has recently been pressing Guatemala at the UN on its human rights record.
Employees of rival TV stations have a fistfight outside a courthouse in a dispute over broadcast frequencies.
Two men throw a bomb at the Taiwanese embassy.
About 30 students set up flaming tire barricades and threw rocks at police to protest curriculum changes and police fired tear gas.
Hundreds of students protesting a teacher's strike demonstrated and threw rocks at passing cars; police fired tear gas and arrested several.
Students seize teaching colleges to protest plans to make them take English and computer science courses.  The seizures end after massive police raids.
Five teenagers who were illegally logging are tortured and killed by parties unknown wearing ski-masks.
Jamaica's telephone workers staged a one-day strike to demand for quicker pace to wage-hike negotiations.
Demonstrators organized by a new student group protest against a television network over its election coverage, accusing it of bias toward the PRI.
While covering rallies for presidential candidate Leonel Fernandez, newswoman was slapped and pushed to ground.
Nine members of Greenpeace occupy the offices of the US state of Texas in Mexico City, protesting plans for a nuclear waste facility near the US-Mexico border.
9 members of Greenpeace stage a 24 hour take over of the Texas state offices in Mexico City, protesting against plans for a nuclear waste plant.
Hundreds of protesters threw rocks and burned tires to protest the treatment of Haitian migrants in the Dominican Republic and at least three people were shot and police fired tear gas.
Cubans were welcoming home "The Five" from imprisonment in the United States and showing support for their return.
Three Greenpeace activists board a ship carrying nuclear waste bound for reprocessing in Japan.  Police make arrests.
Protesters march from Oaxaca and arrive in Mexico City to demonstrate against the governor of Oaxaca, whom they accuse of rigging elections and using force against them.
Five men armed with guns/machetes robbed six tourists and killed a gardner.
An armed gang kidnaps two European tourists, setting off a national crisis.  Hostages are released after ransom is paid.
An armed gang kidnaps two Dutch tourists, demanding ransom.
A town bureau was stoned.
A gang of 20 men robs a train.
The leader of a leftist Indian group is assassinated by gunmen on motorcycles.
Miners strike and riot against Triton Minera to demand better pay and health care.

target: Truck driver carrying migrants and his assistant
issuenote: Haitian demonstrators protested the death of migrants who suffocated in truck entering the D.R., 2 died during demonstrations.
A demonstration against the U.N. envoy and Aristide was held by the Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti.
Gunmen spray the UN building with gunfire on the eve of the election.
Students occupy a dozen buildings on the UNAM campus to demand changes in university policies and administration. They also call for the release of detained student leaders arrested for a strike.

1000 student supporters of the UNAM student strike protest on the one year anniversary of the police raid that ended that event. Protesters, including some members of the strike, detain 33 staff and faculty.
A rebel group opens fire on a USAF base during a visit to Panama by President Bush.  There are no casualties.
Unknown gunmen fire at the US embassy and at the residence of US Marines that guard the embassy in two separate attacks.
Two grenades are thrown at the US embassy.  No one claims credit for the attack.
Hundreds of protesters march to the US embassy and attack police with concrete blocks, metal bars, and firecrackers to protest against a visit by President Bush.  Police respond with tear gas.
Mayan indians protested against President Bush.
Protesters demonstrate for an array of causes during a visit by the US president.  Some denounce free trade, some demand local pay raises, others decry a road ring around the capital.
About 50 protesters gather during a visit by US Secretary of State Powell to decry the Central American Free Trade Agreement.
Demonstrators hurling fireworks chase the US ambassador out of a fair over comments he made criticizing the Nicaraguan Supreme Court for allowing Daniel Ortega to seek another term.
Honduran women demonstrated outside the U.S. Embassy, demanding that Miami authorities release a Honduran woman who is a key witness in a passport scam investigation.
A group of Indians march in front of the US embassy to protest the execution of a man in Arizona, and demanding the withdrawal of US troops from Honduras.

Over 100 Hondurans and 6 Americans protest in front of the US embassy, demanding help in the search for the remains of a US priest killed 15 years earlier in a battle between army forces and leftist guerillas.
Drivers were protesting Uber.
